ummer Olympics|Team]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[1988 Summer Olympics|1988 Seoul]]|[[Basketball at the 1988 Summer Olympics|Team]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2004 Summer Olympics|2004 Athens]]|[[Basketball at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|Team]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA Basketball World Cup|FIBA World Cup]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1954 FIBA World Championship|1954 Brazil]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1986 FIBA World Championship|1986 Spain]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1994 FIBA World Championship|1994 Canada]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2010 FIBA World Championship|2010 Turkey]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2014 FIBA Basketball World Cup|2014 Spain]]|}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[1950 FIBA World Championship|1950 Argentina]]|}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[1959 FIBA World Championship|1959 Chile]]|}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[1982 FIBA World Championship|1982 Colombia]]|}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[1974 FIBA World Championship|1974 Puerto Rico]]|}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[1990 FIBA World Championship|1990 Argentina]]|}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[1998 FIBA World Championship|1998 Greece]]|}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2006 FIBA World Championship|2006 Japan]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA AmeriCup]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1992 Tournament of the Americas|1992 United States]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1993 Tournament of the Americas|1993 Puerto Rico]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1997 Tournament of the Americas|1997 Uruguay]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1999 Tournament of the Americas|1999 Puerto Rico]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2003 Tournament of the Americas|2003 Puerto Rico]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2007 FIBA Americas Championship|2007 United States]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2017 FIBA AmeriCup|2017 Argentina]]|}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[1989 Tournament of the Americas|1989 Mexico]]|}}\n}}\n\nThe '''USA Basketball Men's National Team''',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usab.com/mens/national-team.aspx|title=USA Men's National Team|publisher=[[USA Basketball]]}}</ref> commonly known as the '''United States men's national basketball team''', is the most successful team in international competition, winning medals in all eighteen Olympic tournaments it has entered, including fifteen golds. In the professional era, the team won the Olympic gold medal in [[Basketball at the 1992 Summer Olympics#Men's Tournament|1992]], [[Basketball at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|1996]], [[Basketball at the 2000 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2000]], [[Basketball at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2008]], [[Basketball at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2012]], and [[Basketball at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2016]]. Two of its gold medal-winning teams were inducted to the [[Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame]] in August 2010 \u2013 the [[1960 United States men's Olympic basketball team|1960 team]], which featured six Hall of Famers (4 players, 2 coaches), and the 1992 [[1992 United States men's Olympic basketball team|\"Dream Team\"]], featuring 14 Hall of Famers (11 players, 3 coaches). The team is currently ranked first in the [[FIBA World Rankings]].\n\nTraditionally composed of amateur players, the U.S. dominated the first decades of international basketball, winning a record seven consecutive Olympic gold medals. However, by the end of the 1980s, American amateurs were no longer competitive against seasoned professionals from the [[Soviet Union national basketball team|Soviet Union]] and [[Yugoslavia national basketball team|Yugoslavia]].<ref name=\"Tyler Benson\">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.bu.edu/guidedhistory/russia-and-its-empires/tyler-benson/|title=The Role of Sports in The Soviet Union|publisher=blogs.bu.edu|author=Tyler Benson}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/readingroom/docs/CIA-RDP80-00810A005600130009-0.pdf|title=Soviet Sports and Intelligence Activities|publisher=Central Intelligence Agency|work=[[Central Intelligence Agency]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/readingroom/docs/CIA-RDP80-00810A005800260002-1.pdf|title=Soviet Sports as an Instrument of Political Propaganda|publisher=Central Intelligence Agency|work=Central Intelligence Agency}}</ref>\n\nIn 1989, [[FIBA]] modified its rules and allowed [[USA Basketball]] to field teams with [[National Basketball Association]] players. The first such team, known as the \"Dream Team\", won the gold medal at the [[Basketball at the 1992 Summer Olympics|1992 Summer Olympics]] in [[Barcelona]], being superior in all matches.<ref name=\"USA Basketball\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usab.com/history/national-team-mens/mens-olympic-games-all-time-results-standings.aspx|title=Men's Olympic Games All-Time Results & Standings|publisher=USA Basketball}}</ref><ref name=\"USA Men's Olympic Team History\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usab.com/mens/national-team/history.aspx|title=USA Men's Olympic Team History|publisher=USA Basketball}}</ref> With the introduction of NBA players, the team was able to spark a second run of dominance in the 1990s.\n\nFacing increased competition, the U.S. failed to win a medal at the [[2002 FIBA World Championship]], finishing sixth. The [[2004 United States men's Olympic basketball team|2004 Olympic team]], being depleted by a number of withdrawals, lost three games on its way to a bronze medal, a record that represented more losses in a single year than the country's Olympic teams had suffered in all previous Olympiads combined.\n\nDetermined to put an end to these failures, USA Basketball initiated a long-term project aimed at creating better, more cohesive teams. The U.S. won its first seven games at the [[2006 FIBA World Championship]] in Japan before losing against [[Greece national basketball team|Greece]] in the semi-finals; ending the competition with the bronze medal. The team won gold two years later \u2013 at the [[Basketball at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2008 Summer Olympics]] \u2013 in a dominant fashion. This success was followed up at the [[2010 FIBA World Championship]], where despite fielding a roster featuring no players from the [[2008 United States men's Olympic basketball team|2008 Olympic team]], the U.S. did not lose a single game en route to defeating host [[Turkey national basketball team|Turkey]] for the gold medal.\n\nThe Americans continued this streak of dominance in the 2010s by going undefeated and capturing gold at the [[Basketball at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2012 Summer Olympics]], and [[2014 FIBA Basketball World Cup|2014 FIBA World Cup]] until [[2019 FIBA World Cup]], where they lost to France in the Quarter-finals, finishing 7th overall. At the [[Basketball at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2016 Summer Olympics]], the team, led by [[Mike Krzyzewski]] for a record third time, won its fifteenth gold medal, making him the most decorated coach in USA Basketball history.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usab.com/history/national-team-mens/games-of-the-xxxith-olympiad-2016.aspx|title=Games of the XXXIth Olympiad -- 2016|publisher=USA Basketball}}</ref><ref name=\"USA Men's Olympic Team History\"/>\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==History==\n===1936\u20131968===\n[[File:USA-USSR.jpg|thumb|left|Game between the U.S. and the [[Soviet Union men's national basketball team|USSR]] in the 1952 Olympics]]\nThe US men were dominant from the first Olympic tournament to hold basketball, held in Berlin in [[Basketball at the 1936 Summer Olympics|1936]], going 5\u20130 to win the gold, and joined by continental neighbors Canada and Mexico on the medal platform. Through the next six tournaments, the United States went undefeated, collecting gold while not losing a single contest in the games held in [[Basketball at the 1948 Summer Olympics|London]], [[Basketball at the 1952 Summer Olympics|Helsinki]], [[Basketball at the 1956 Summer Olympics|Melbourne]], [[Basketball at the 1960 Summer Olympics|Rome]], [[Basketball at the 1964 Summer Olympics|Tokyo]], and [[Basketball at the 1968 Summer Olympics|Mexico City]]. Participation in these tournaments were limited to amateurs, but the US teams during this period featured players who would later go on to become superstars in professional basketball, including [[50 Greatest Players in NBA History|all-time greats]] [[Bill Russell]], [[Oscar Robertson]], [[Jerry West]], and [[Jerry Lucas]]; the latter three competed on the 1960 Rome team often credited as the best U.S. roster until the formation of the 1992 Dream Team.<ref>[http://www.usabasketball.com/history/moly_1960.html ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071014023857/http://www.usabasketball.com/history/moly_1960.html |date=October 14, 2007 }}</ref>\n\n[[Alex Groza]] and [[Ralph Beard]], both briefly NBA stars, made the 1948 squad as [[Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball|Kentucky Wildcats]], with 3-time [[Oklahoma State Cowboys basketball|Oklahoma State]] All-American and 6-time AAU All-American, and Hall of Famer [[Bob Kurland]] leading the way. The 1952 team included big man [[Clyde Lovellette]] of the University of Kansas, a future Hall of Famer and NBA star. Kurland once again led the team to victory. The 1956 team was led by San Francisco Dons Bill Russell and K.C. Jones.\n\nThe 1960 team included nine future NBA players, including not just Robertson, Lucas and West, but Bob Boozer, Adrian Smith [1966 All Star game MVP], Jay Arnette, [[Terry Dischinger]], Rookie of the Year in 1963, and another Hall of Famer in [[Walt Bellamy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/event/p/cid//sid/2945/_/1960_Olympic_Games_Tournament_for_Men/index.html |title=2000 Olympic Games : Tournament for Men |publisher=archive.fiba.com |date= |accessdate=2010-08-27}}</ref>\n\n===1972\u20131988===\nThe 1972 Olympic men's basketball gold medal game, marking the first ever loss for the US in Olympic play, is arguably the most controversial in Olympic history. The United States rode their seven consecutive gold medals and 63\u20130 Olympic record to Munich for the [[1972 Summer Olympics]]. The team won its first eight games in convincing fashion, setting up a final against the Soviet Union, holding a 6\u20130 advantage over the Soviets in Olympic play.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/event/p/cid//sid/2945/_/1972_Olympic_Games_Tournament_for_Men/index.html |title=2000 Olympic Games : Tournament for Men |publisher=archive.fiba.com |date= |accessdate=2010-08-27}}</ref>\n\nWith three seconds left in the gold medal game, American forward [[Doug Collins (basketball)|Doug Collins]] sank two free throws after being hit hard by a Soviet player to put the Americans up 50\u201349. Immediately following Collins' free throws, the Soviets inbounded the ball and failed to score. Soviet coaches claimed that they had requested a timeout before Collins' foul shots. The referees ordered the clock reset to three seconds and the game's final seconds replayed. The horn sounded as a length-of-the-court Soviet pass was being released from the inbounding player, the pass missed its mark, and the American players began celebrating.\n\nNevertheless, the final three seconds were replayed for a third time. This time, the Soviets' [[Alexander Belov]] and the USA's [[Kevin Joyce (basketball)|Kevin Joyce]] and [[James Forbes (basketball)|Jim Forbes]] went up for the pass, and Belov caught the long pass from Ivan Edeshko near the American basket. Belov then laid the ball in for the winning points as the buzzer sounded. The US players voted unanimously to refuse their silver medals, and at least one team member, [[Kenneth Davis (basketball)|Kenny Davis]], has directed in his will that his heirs are never to accept the medals, even posthumously.<ref>{{cite news|author=Gary Smith |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1003894/6/index.htm |title=Pieces of Silver |work=Sports Illustrated|date=1992-06-15 |accessdate=2010-08-27}}</ref><ref name=espn1>''By Frank Saraceno''. [http://espn.go.com/classic/s/Classic_1972_usa_ussr_gold_medal_hoop.html Classic 1972 USA vs. USSR Basketball game.] // espn.go.com (August 6, 2004)</ref> It was later revealed that game officials might have been bribed by the [[Communist party of the Soviet Union|Communist party]].<ref name=joursport1>''Chris Elzey (American Studies Purdue University)'' [http://www.la84foundation.org/SportsLibrary/JSH/JSH2002/JSH2903/jsh2903ag.pdf \u00ab03 Seconds From Gold\u00bb (2002)] \u00abJournal of Sports History\u00bb (vol 29, issue 3, page 518\u2014522) // la84foundation.org</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=120 years, 120 stories (Part 15): Soviets beat the Americans amidst controversies involving communist judges|url=http://sports-nova.com/2016/03/04/120-years-120-stories-part-15-soviets-beat-americans-amidst-controversies-involving-communist-judges/|accessdate=March 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter the controversial loss in Munich, 1976 saw [[Dean Smith]] coach the US to a 7\u20130 record and its eighth Olympic gold medal [[Basketball at the 1976 Summer Olympics|in Montreal]]. The success at this tournament pushed the USA's all-time Olympic record to an impressive 78\u20131.\n\nThe [[Soviet\u2013Afghan War|Soviet invasion of Afghanistan]] prompted the United States and 66 other countries to [[1980 Summer Olympics boycott|boycott]] the [[1980 Summer Olympics|1980 Olympics]] in Moscow.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/event/p/cid//sid/2945/_/1980_Olympic_Games_Tournament_for_Men/index.html |title=2000 Olympic Games : Tournament for Men |publisher=archive.fiba.com |date= |accessdate=2010-08-27}}</ref>\n\nThe 1980 U.S. team, which featured a number of future NBA players, was the youngest American national team ever assembled. This team featured: [[Mark Aguirre]], [[Rolando Blackman]], [[Sam Bowie]], [[Michael Brooks (basketball)|Michael Brooks]], [[Bill Hanzlik]], [[Alton Lister]], [[Rodney McCray (basketball)|Rodney McCray]], [[Isiah Thomas]], [[Darnell Valentine]], [[Danny Vranes]], [[Buck Williams]] and [[Al Wood]].<ref name=\"Usabasketball.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.usabasketball.com/mens/national/moly_1980.html |title=USAB: Games of the XXIInd Olympiad \u2013 1980 |publisher=Usabasketball.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120807123328/http://www.usabasketball.com/mens/national/moly_1980.html |archive-date=2012-08-07 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> Unable to compete in the Olympics due to the boycott, it instead participated in the \"[[Gold Medal Series]]\", a series of games against NBA all-star teams in various U.S. cities, recording a 5\u20131 record.<ref name=\"Usabasketball.com\" /> It was coached by [[Dave Gavitt]].\n\n[[Michael Jordan]], [[Patrick Ewing]], and [[Chris Mullin (basketball)|Chris Mullin]], future members of the '92 Dream Team, made their Olympic debuts in 1984. Jordan led the team with 17.1 points per game, and [[Bob Knight]] coached the team to an 8\u20130 record and another Olympic gold.\n\nThe 1988 U.S. team had a roster of collegians aged 20-23 that included future NBA all-stars [[David Robinson]], [[Danny Manning]], and [[Mitch Richmond]]. The team came up short, winning the bronze medal. The American team lost to the gold medal winner Soviet Union in the semifinals, but then regrouped and went on to beat Australia 78\u201349 in the bronze medal game. [[Dan Majerle]] led the team in scoring, averaging 14.1 points per game. This was the last time the American Olympic Team consisted of amateur college players.\n\n===1992\u20132000===\nThe decade started with a semifinal loss to Yugoslavia in the [[1990 FIBA World Championship]], followed by another semifinal defeat to Puerto Rico in the [[Basketball at the 1991 Pan American Games|1991 Pan American Games]] in Havana. The 1990 championship marked the last time that the U.S. was represented by college players at a major international tournament (World Championship & Olympics).\n\n[[File:Cazzaro Jordan.jpg|thumb|right|[[Michael Jordan]] as part of the Dream Team during the 1992 Olympics]]\nThe decades-long use of \"shamateurs\" by the Soviet Union, [[Yugoslavia national basketball team|Yugoslavia]] and other international teams prompted [[FIBA]] to modify its rules and allow [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] players in the [[Basketball at the 1992 Summer Olympics|1992 Olympics]] and beyond.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2012/07/11/unique-cast-of-characters-responsible-for-building-dream-team/|title=Unique cast of characters responsible for building Dream Team|work=[[New York Post]]|author=Marc Berman|date=11 July 2012|accessdate=17 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usab.com/history/why-can-pros-complete-in-international-events.aspx|title=Why Can Pros Compete in International Events?|publisher=USA Basketball|author=Jan Hubbard|accessdate=15 April 2018}}</ref> The team assembled by USA Basketball for the [[Basketball at the 1992 Summer Olympics|tournament in Barcelona in 1992]] was one of the most illustrious collections of talent assembled in the history of international sport. Of the twelve players on the team, ten were named in 1996 among the [[50 Greatest Players in NBA History]], the [[National Basketball Association|NBA's]] official list of the 50 greatest players of the league's first 50 years. [[Magic Johnson]] and [[Larry Bird]] served as co-captains.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iLkDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA48&lpg=PA48&dq=larry+bird+co-captain&source=bl&ots=FDxmIyIYPv&sig=NU7xKpPb230BAvZVEaM83642rzw&hl=en&ei=zj-3TN_PCYK8sQOgmdycCQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CBoQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=larry%20bird%20co-captain&f=false |title=Jet Magazine Jul 13, 1992 |publisher=Johnson Publishing Company |accessdate=2010-10-14}}</ref>\n\nBecause of this star line-up, the team's games usually featured opposing teams asking for pregame photos and autographs with their U.S. opponents. The USA team was so much better than the competition that head coach Chuck Daly did not call a single timeout during the tournament. The 1992 Dream Team won by an average of 43.8 points, an Olympic record, and the closest a team came to challenging the U.S. was Croatia, which was beaten by 32.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/event/p/cid//sid/2945/_/1992_Olympic_Games_Tournament_for_Men/index.html |title=2000 Olympic Games : Tournament for Men |publisher=archive.fiba.com |date= |accessdate=2010-08-27}}</ref> [[Michael Jordan]] and [[Scottie Pippen]] became the first players to win both [[1992 NBA Finals|NBA championship]] and Olympic gold medal in the same year, having played for the [[Chicago Bulls]].\n\nRegarding drug-testing the athletes, according to USA Basketball spokesman Craig Miller, \"Since 1990, all of our teams have been tested in competition. I believe since around 1988 we have also been subject to out-of-competition testing. We have been 100 percent fully compliant with USADA and WADA.\"<ref>[http://myespn.go.com/blogs/truehoop/0-33-182/Team-USA--Yes--We-re-Drug-Tested.html?post=true] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228211601/http://myespn.go.com/blogs/truehoop/0-33-182/Team-USA--Yes--We-re-Drug-Tested.html?post=true |date=February 28, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nThe United States fielded another team composed of NBA players in the [[1994 FIBA World Championship|1994 World Championship]], held in [[Toronto, Ontario]], Canada. This was an entirely new roster, as [[USA Basketball]] elected to showcase stars who were not present at the 1992 Olympics. Composed primarily of younger NBA players, the team lacked the widespread appeal of its predecessor but nevertheless continued its dominance. Those players were [[Derrick Coleman]], [[Joe Dumars]], [[Kevin Johnson (basketball)|Kevin Johnson]], [[Larry Johnson (basketball, born 1969)|Larry Johnson]], [[Shawn Kemp]], [[Dan Majerle]], [[Reggie Miller]], [[Alonzo Mourning]], [[Shaquille O'Neal]], [[Mark Price]], [[Steve Smith (basketball)|Steve Smith]] and [[Dominique Wilkins]]. Coached by [[Don Nelson]] of the [[Golden State Warriors]], this team easily captured the gold medal in tournament play.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/event/p/sid/2913/tid/379/_/1994_World_Championship_for_Men_/index.html |title=1994 World Championship for Men |publisher=.fiba.com archive|date=1994-08-14 |accessdate=2010-08-27}}</ref> The team was referred to as the \"Dream Team II\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Araton|first=Harvey|title=BASKETBALL; Dream Team Ends Its Sequel Predictably|date=August 15, 1994|newspaper=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/08/15/sports/basketball-dream-team-ends-its-sequel-predictably.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69DFRSs2h?url=http://www.nytimes.com/1994/08/15/sports/basketball-dream-team-ends-its-sequel-predictably.html?pagewanted=all|archivedate=July 17, 2012|url-status=live|access-date=May 22, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe third team composed of NBA players participated in the [[1996 Summer Olympics]] held in [[Atlanta]]. The star quality of the team was impressive as it featured five members of the original Dream Team (Barkley, Malone, Pippen, Robinson, and Stockton), plus two other members of the NBA 50 Greatest Players list, [[Hakeem Olajuwon]] and [[Shaquille O'Neal]]. [[Lenny Wilkens]] coached the team.\n\nThe Americans won another gold medal with an average margin of victory of 31.8 points per game. They captured the gold medal after defeating [[Yugoslavia national basketball team|Yugoslavia]] 95\u201369.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/event/p/cid//sid/2945/_/1996_Olympic_Games_Tournament_for_Men/index.html |title=2000 Olympic Games : Tournament for Men |publisher=archive.fiba.com |date= |accessdate=2010-08-27}}</ref> With Atlanta being home to the [[Atlanta Hawks|Hawks]], these games were the first Olympics to take place in a city with an NBA team since the league started allowing its players to compete in the Olympics.\n\nThe team was commonly referred to as the \"Dream Team III\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vibe.com/article/nba-tv-dream-team-documentary-vibe-1996-dream-team-iii-cover |title=VIBE Magazine \u2013 1996 |publisher=vibe.com |date= |accessdate=2012-07-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Rhoden|first=William C.|title=Sports of The Times;Competitors Without a Competition|date=July 23, 1996|newspaper=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/07/23/sports/sports-of-the-times-competitors-without-a-competition.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101130122003/http://www.nytimes.com/1996/07/23/sports/sports-of-the-times-competitors-without-a-competition.html?pagewanted=all|archivedate=November 30, 2010|url-status=live|access-date=February 14, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe [[1998 FIBA World Championship|1998 World Championship]] in [[Athens, Greece]] was different from the previous teams, as none of its players were current members of NBA teams. Because of [[1998\u201399 NBA lockout|a labor dispute that led to a lockout]], no active NBA players were permitted to compete in the tournament. The 12 NBA players picked before the lockout were [[Tim Duncan]], [[Tim Hardaway]], [[Vin Baker]], [[Gary Payton]], [[Terrell Brandon]], [[Kevin Garnett]], [[Tom Gugliotta]], [[Grant Hill]], [[Allan Houston]], [[Christian Laettner]], [[Glen Rice]], and [[Chris Webber]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/1998/07/07/archive/main13393.shtml |title=NBA Stars Locked Out Of Team USA |publisher=cbs.com |date= 1998-07-07|accessdate=2010-09-21}}</ref>\n\nThe replacement team was composed largely of players from American colleges, the minor-league [[Continental Basketball Association]], or European pro leagues. The unheralded roster captured a bronze medal, considered a solid achievement given its lack of top-notch talent.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usabasketball.com/mens/national/mwc_1998.html |title=THIRTEENTH WORLD CHAMPIONSHIP \u2013 1998 |publisher=usabasketball.com |date= |accessdate=2010-09-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100905002640/http://www.usabasketball.com/mens/national/mwc_1998.html |archive-date=2010-09-05 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> The team was nicknamed the \"Dirty Dozen\" for its work ethic and teamwork. Undrafted free agent [[Brad Miller (basketball)|Brad Miller]] became a two-time [[NBA All-Star]]. Some of the other team members\u2014including [[Trajan Langdon]], [[Kiwane Garris]], [[David Wood (basketball)|David Wood]] and [[Michael Hawkins (basketball)|Michael Hawkins]]\u2014had brief spells in the NBA. All went on to have careers in Europe, with Langdon being named to the [[Euroleague]]'s [[ULEB Euroleague 2001\u201310 All-Decade Team|All-Decade Team]] for the 2000s.\n\nDuring the late 1990s, international basketball began to gather attention as more and more foreign players became stars in the NBA. Therefore, the 2000 U.S. team had the enormous task of proving that American basketball could remain the best in the world. The new team that was assembled again featured [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] players, but this time few of them were considered to be true superstars, as several elite players elected not to participate.\n\nThe U.S. team participated in the [[2000 Summer Olympics|2000 Olympics]] in [[Sydney]], Australia and was coached by [[Rudy Tomjanovich]]. It won its first two games by lopsided margins, but faced more difficult competition thereafter. In a preliminary game against [[Lithuania men's national basketball team|Lithuania]], the U.S. team won 85\u201376, marking the first time a team of professional American players failed to win by double digits. Two games later, in a 106\u201394 victory over [[France national basketball team|France]], [[Vince Carter]] pulled off one of the most famous dunks in basketball history, jumping over the 7&nbsp;ft 2 in (2.18 m) [[France national basketball team|French]] [[center (basketball)|center]] [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Weis]] on his way to the basket. (The French media would dub Carter's feat ''{{lang|fr|le dunk de la mort}}''\u2014\"the dunk of death\".)\n\nA shock came in the semifinals when the United States defeated Lithuania by the close score of 85\u201383. Lithuanian star (and future NBA player, first with the [[Indiana Pacers]] and later with the [[Golden State Warriors]]) [[\u0160ar\u016bnas Jasikevi\u010dius]] missed a desperation 3 at the buzzer that would have won the game.\n\nThe closeness of the semifinal game was so shocking that [[Olympics on NBC|NBC]] took the unusual step of showing the gold medal game live rather than on [[broadcast delay|tape delay]]. (The game started around 2 p.m. Sydney time on Sunday, October 1, which is late Saturday evening in the USA. NBC originally planned to show the game almost 24 hours later during its Sunday [[prime time]] broadcast.) The USA won the gold medal against France in a close game, 85\u201375. Though the US went undefeated on its way to the gold medal, the team began to lose its aura of invincibility for the first time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/event/p/cid//sid/2945/_/2000_Olympic_Games_Tournament_for_Men/index.html |title=2000 Olympic Games : Tournament for Men |publisher=archive.fiba.com |date= |accessdate=2010-08-27}}</ref>\n\n===2002\u20132004===\nThe 2002 team competed in the [[2002 FIBA World Championship|World Championship]] in Indianapolis, Indiana, USA. Coached by George Karl, the team finished a surprisingly disappointing sixth in the competition. During the tournament, Argentina defeated the US in the second preliminary round group stage, thus becoming the first team ever to defeat a USA team composed of NBA players. Yugoslavia knocked out the US in the quarterfinals, becoming the first team ever to defeat USA team of NBA players in knockout stage. Then Spain repeated the outcome in the 5th place playoff.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/event/p/cid//sid/2911/_/2002_FIBA_World_Championship_for_Men/index.html |title=1986 World Championship for Men |publisher=archive.fiba.com |date= |accessdate=2010-08-27}}</ref> To a greater degree than in 2000, a number of top NBA players declined to participate, forcing USA Basketball to resort to picking mostly second-tier players.\nGeorge Karl had a dispute with [[Paul Pierce]], one of the few superstars on the team, which led to Karl benching Pierce, the team's leading scorer, in Team USA's final game. The group has been considered as one of sport's greatest flops, as they failed to produce as previous teams had. The United States lost 3 games in the tournament to countries with current or future NBA stars, like Argentina (led by [[Manu Gin\u00f3bili]]), Yugoslavia (led by [[Peja Stojakovi\u0107]] and [[Vlade Divac]]) and Spain (led by [[Pau Gasol]]).\n\nTwo NBA superstars, [[Ray Allen]] and [[Jason Kidd]], accepted roles to play on the World Championship team, but were unable to play on that team due to injuries. Many other superstars, including [[Kobe Bryant]], [[Shaquille O'Neal]], and [[Kevin Garnett]], turned down invitations to play in that tournament.\n\n[[File:SCG - USA - USA training.jpg|thumb|right|Team USA members warm up before the game in 2004 in [[Belgrade Arena]]]]\nThe close outcome of 2000 and the humiliating results of 2002 prompted a number of NBA superstars to agree to join the team for the [[FIBA Americas Championship 2003]], dubbed as the  Dream Team IV,<ref>{{cite web|author=Will Leitch |url=http://www.sportsonearth.com/article/186889450/usa-basketball-rio-olympics-dream-team |title=The Dream Team hangs over every USA basketball team. |publisher=Sports on Earth |date=2016-06-29 |accessdate=2017-03-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/sport/sonst/basketball-dream-team-iv-loest-tickets-fuer-sydney-a-32826-amp.html |title=Basketball: \"Dream Team IV\" l\u00f6st Tickets f\u00fcr Sydney \u2013 SPIEGEL ONLINE |website=Spiegel.de |date=1999-07-24 |accessdate=2017-03-06}}</ref>  which the squad was required to participate in to qualify for the [[2004 Summer Olympics]]. The team easily cruised to a first-place finish, earning it a spot in [[Athens]], Greece, the following summer.\n\nHowever, the dominant team that competed in 2003 could not be kept together. Nine of its 12 players elected not to participate in Athens. The new team consisted of some young NBA stars early in their careers, such as [[Dwyane Wade]], [[LeBron James]] and [[Carmelo Anthony]]. Only [[Richard Jefferson]], [[Tim Duncan]] and [[Allen Iverson]] were part of the 2003 [[2003 Tournament of the Americas|FIBA Americas San Juan]] gold medal team. The team was coached by [[Larry Brown (basketball)|Larry Brown]].\n\nAfter struggles in several exhibition matches, the vulnerability of the 2004 team was confirmed when [[Puerto Rican National Basketball Team|Puerto Rico]] defeated them 92\u201373, from which they earned the nickname \"Nightmare team\" (as mock opposed to the Dream Team concept),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/espn/page2/story?page=simmons/040804 |title=Page 2 : This Dream Team is doomed |website=ESPN.com |date=1999-02-22 |accessdate=2017-03-06}}</ref> in the first game of the [[2004 Summer Olympics|Olympic tournament]] in Athens. The 19 point defeat was the most lopsided loss for the US in the history of international competition. After the game, Larry Brown had strong comments about his coaching performance: \"I'm humiliated, not for the loss -- I can always deal with wins and losses -- but I'm disappointed because I had a job to do as a coach, to get us to understand how we're supposed to play as a team and act as a team, and I don't think we did that\".<ref>{{cite web|title=U.S.: 3-for-24 from 3-point range|url=http://www.espn.com/olympics/summer04/basketball/news/story?id=1859825|website=ESPN|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=October 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter winning close games against [[Greece national basketball team|Greece]] and Australia, The USA fell to [[Lithuania men's national basketball team|Lithuania]], dropping to 2\u20132 in the Olympic tournament. Even after an 89\u201353 win over Angola, the Americans entered the knockout rounds in fourth place due to goal average, the lowest seed of their group. The Americans faced undefeated Spain in their quarterfinal game, winning 102\u201394.\n\nHowever, the semifinal match saw the team defeated by [[Argentina national basketball team|Argentina]] 89\u201381, ending the United States' hold on the gold medal. The USA did rebound to capture the bronze medal by defeating Lithuania.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/event/p/cid//sid/2945/_/2004_Olympic_Games_Tournament_for_Men/index.html |title=2000 Olympic Games : Tournament for Men |publisher=archive.fiba.com |date= |accessdate=2010-08-27}}</ref>  Still, it marked only the third time that an American team failed to win gold (excluding the 1980 Moscow Olympics boycott), and the first time for an American team composed of NBA players.\n\n===2006\u20132016===\nFollowing the disappointments in 2002 and 2004, USA Basketball appointed [[Jerry Colangelo]] to be solely responsible for selecting the team. Colangelo made it clear that he would ask players for a three-year commitment\u2014the [[2006 FIBA World Championship]] and the [[Basketball at the 2008 Summer Olympics|2008 Summer Olympics]]. In the 2006 Worlds, the team was eliminated by Greece in the semifinal, losing the game 101\u201395. The head coach was [[Duke Blue Devils men's basketball|Duke University]]'s [[Mike Krzyzewski]], with assistants [[Jim Boeheim]], [[Mike D'Antoni]], and [[Nate McMillan]]. While some prominent players, such as [[Tim Duncan]] and [[Kevin Garnett]], stated that they did not plan to play for the team, superstars [[Dwyane Wade]], [[Kobe Bryant]] and [[LeBron James]] publicly announced their commitment for the 2006 Worlds and the ensuing 2008 Olympics. Wade, James and [[Carmelo Anthony]] were named captains of the 2006 USA World Championship Team.\n\n[[File:TeamUSA2008bball.jpg|thumb|The USA players standing prior to a game against China in the [[Basketball at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|Beijing Olympics]]]]\nThe United States Team, dubbed Dream Team V or the Redeem Team, dominated Group B in pool play, defeating [[China national basketball team|China]], [[Angola national basketball team|Angola]], [[Greece national basketball team|Greece]], [[2006 FIBA World Championship|world champion]] [[Spain national basketball team|Spain]], and [[Germany national basketball team|Germany]] by an average of 32.2 points. After finishing first in their group, the USA earned the right to play the fourth-place finishers in Group A, [[Australia men's national basketball team|Australia]]. The United States soundly defeated Australia 116\u201385 in the quarterfinal. Next up for the Americans in the semifinals was the [[Basketball at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's basketball|2004 Olympic gold medalist]] Argentina, led by [[Manu Gin\u00f3bili]] \u2013 the team that had beaten them in the semifinals four years prior. However, Gin\u00f3bili was hobbled by an ankle injury and only played sparing minutes in the first half. Behind Carmelo Anthony's 21 points, the USA defeated Argentina 101\u201381 to reach the gold medal game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/event/p/cid//sid/2945/_/2008_Olympic_Games_Tournament_for_Men/index.html |title=2000 Olympic Games : Tournament for Men |publisher=archive.fiba.com |date= |accessdate=2010-08-27}}</ref>\n\nOn August 24, the United States defeated Spain 118\u2013107 to capture the Olympic gold medal with the electrifying spark by team U.S.A. leading scorer Dwyane Wade adding 27 points with 4 3's and 100% shooting inside the line. The victory ended an eight-year drought at major international competitions (Olympics & World Championships) with the first win since [[Basketball at the 2000 Summer Olympics|2000]].\n\nDue to winning gold at the 2008 Olympics, the USA automatically qualified for the World Championships. The USA had not won the FIBA World Championship since [[1994 FIBA World Championship|1994]]. It was initially believed that there would be only 2\u20133 spots available with most players returning from the 2008 Olympic team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://insider.espn.go.com/nba/insider/columns/story?columnist=sheridan_chris&page=coachk-090721|title=Coach Krzyzewski putting legacy at risk|work=ESPN.com|date=2009-07-22|first=Chris|last=Sheridan|accessdate=2010-09-15}}</ref> However, by early July 2010, all ten invited players declined to participate, due to injury, free agency, rest, or personal commitments.<ref name=id5372600>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/oly/olybb/news/story?id=5372600|title='08 Olympians to skip basketball worlds|work=ESPN.com|first=Chris|last=Sheridan|accessdate=2010-09-15}}</ref> Due to the roster being filled with 12 new players and the lack of star power, the team was dubbed the \"B Team\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Thamel|first=Pete|title=Not the Redeem Team, but Still Chasing a Dream|date=July 22, 2010|newspaper=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/23/sports/basketball/23teamusa.html|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69WmL3QxD?url=http://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/23/sports/basketball/23teamusa.html?_r=1|archivedate=July 29, 2012|url-status=live|access-date=February 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Also, the coaches were criticized for selecting too many guards and inexperienced players, and not enough tall players.\n\nHowever, the team won all five of its preliminary games, four of those by double digits (the exception being the win against Brazil by 2 points). The success continued in the knockout stage with victories by 55, 10 and 15. In the [[2010 FIBA World Championship Final]], the USA beat host nation [[Turkey national basketball team|Turkey]] by 17 points and won the gold medal.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/09/13/sports/basketball/13fiba.html|title=Durant Lifts Americans Back to Top at Worlds|date=2010-08-12|work=New York Times|accessdate=2010-09-13|first=Pete|last=Thamel}}</ref> Tournament MVP [[Kevin Durant]] broke several Team USA scoring records (most points in a tournament-205, most points in a single game-38, and average points per game-22.8). In addition, [[Lamar Odom]] became the first player to win the NBA and FIBA World championships in the same year.\n\nTeam USA executive director [[Jerry Colangelo]] has said he's open to anyone from the 2010 team to play in future tournaments.<ref name=id5372600/>\n\n[[File:Bryant on the ball.jpg|thumb|right|The 2012 team practicing in Washington, D.C.]]\nThe US team clinched a berth in the [[Basketball at the 2012 Summer Olympics|2012 Olympics]] in London by winning the 2010 World Championship. The Olympic team lost some players to injuries who might have made the team and appeared to be short on big men. Their roster featured five players returning from the 2008 Olympic team and five others from the 2010 World Championship team.\n\nThe US went undefeated but appeared vulnerable at times in winning five exhibition games. They finished the tournament with a perfect 8\u20130 record, defeating opponents by an average of 32 points while trailing in the fourth quarter only once. The Americans often played with a [[Small ball (basketball)|small lineup]] that emphasized speed, quickness, and outside shooting. The team set an Olympic single-game record with 156 points scored against [[Nigeria national basketball team|Nigeria]] in the preliminary round. In a rematch of the 2008 finals, Team USA again narrowly defeated [[Spain national basketball team|Spain]] to capture the gold.\n\nThis was announced as the final Olympic Games for Kobe Bryant.<ref name=finalgames>{{cite news|last=Hoffman|first=Benjamin|title=A Close Game, a Statement by James|date=August 12, 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|url=http://london2012.nytimes.com/basketball/mens/gold-medal-game-1}}</ref> By winning the gold medal, the USA automatically qualified for the [[2014 FIBA World Cup]].\n\nThe United States had automatically qualified for the World Cup by virtue of the gold medal won by their [[2012 United States men's Olympic basketball team|2012 Olympic team]]. The Americans were considered favorites to win the [[2014 FIBA Basketball World Cup|World Cup]]. The roster was filled with two players returning from the 2012 Olympic team, three from the 2010 FIBA Championship Team, while seven other NBA players made their senior international debuts. The 2014 roster featured four players 6 feet 10 inches (2.08 m) or larger, the most of any USA team since [[Mike Krzyzewski]] began coaching the team in 2006. The team was also the youngest American team since [[1992 United States men's Olympic basketball team|1992]] when NBA players were first allowed on the team; the average player was 24.08 years old, roughly a half-year younger than their 2010 team.\n\nThe team advanced to the knockout phase after starting the tournament 5\u20130 during the group stage. They went undefeated 9\u20130 in the tournament, winning by an average margin of 33.0 points. The United States was just the third country in World Cup history to repeat as champions. Combined with their 2010 World Championship along with gold by their 2008 and 2012 Olympic teams, they also became the first country in FIBA basketball history to win four consecutive major titles. The United States defeated [[Serbia national basketball team|Serbia]] in the [[2014 FIBA Basketball World Cup Final|World Cup Final]] by 37 points and clinched a berth for the [[Basketball at the 2016 Summer Olympics|2016 Summer Olympics]].\n\nMultiple withdrawals (largely triggered by a freak injury to [[Paul George]] in a pre-2014 World Cup scrimmage) left the 2016 U.S. team with just two players with prior Olympic experience (Durant and Anthony). The Americans seemed vulnerable in the preliminary round, narrowly defeating Australia, Serbia, and France by a combined 16 points. However, the team gained momentum in the quarterfinal match against Argentina, winning 105\u201378. The U.S. team then defeated [[Spain men's national basketball team|Spain]] in the semifinals setting up a rematch versus Serbia in the gold medal game. The Americans proved their superiority, easily defeating their rival by 30 points. The team averaged 100.9 points (with an average margin of victory at 22.5 points) a game with Anthony (he won a record third straight Olympic gold medal) and Durant as top scorers. Krzyzewski stepped down as the most decorated coach in USA Basketball history, winning three Olympic gold medals and two FIBA World Cups.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usab.com/history/national-team-mens/games-of-the-xxxith-olympiad-2016.aspx|title=Games of the XXXIth Olympiad -- 2016|publisher=USA Basketball}}</ref>\n\n==Honors==\n'''[[Basketball at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]'''\n* '''Gold medalists''' (15): [[Basketball at the 1936 Summer Olympics|1936]], [[Basketball at the 1948 Summer Olympics|1948]], [[Basketball at the 1952 Summer Olympics|1952]], [[Basketball at the 1956 Summer Olympics|1956]], [[Basketball at the 1960 Summer Olympics|1960]], [[Basketball at the 1964 Summer Olympics|1964]], [[Basketball at the 1968 Summer Olympics|1968]], [[Basketball at the 1976 Summer Olympics#Men's Tournament|1976]], [[Basketball at the 1984 Summer Olympics#Men's Tournament|1984]], [[Basketball at the 1992 Summer Olympics#Men's Tournament|1992]], [[Basketball at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|1996]], [[Basketball at the 2000 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2000]], [[Basketball at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2008]], [[Basketball at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2012]], [[Basketball at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2016]]\n* Silver medalists (1): [[Basketball at the 1972 Summer Olympics|1972]]\n* Bronze medalists (2): [[Basketball at the 1988 Summer Olympics#Men's Tournament|1988]], [[Basketball at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2004]]\n\n'''[[FIBA Basketball World Cup|FIBA World Cup]]'''\n* '''Champions''' (5): [[1954 FIBA World Championship|1954]], [[1986 FIBA World Championship|1986]], [[1994 FIBA World Championship|1994]], [[2010 FIBA World Championship|2010]], [[2014 FIBA Basketball World Cup|2014]]\n* Runners-up (3): [[1950 FIBA World Championship|1950]], [[1959 FIBA World Championship|1959]], [[1982 FIBA World Championship|1982]]\n* Third place (4): [[1974 FIBA World Championship|1974]], [[1990 FIBA World Championship|1990]], [[1998 FIBA World Championship|1998]], [[2006 FIBA World Championship|2006]]\n\n'''[[FIBA AmeriCup]]'''\n* '''Champions''' (7): [[1992 Tournament of the Americas|1992]], [[1993 Tournament of the Americas|1993]], [[1997 Tournament of the Americas|1997]], [[1999 Tournament of the Americas|1999]], [[2003 Tournament of the Americas|2003]], [[2007 FIBA Americas Championship|2007]], [[2017 FIBA AmeriCup|2017]]\n* Runners-up (1): [[1989 Tournament of the Americas|1989]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!Competition !!{{gold1}} !!{{silver2}} !!{{bronze3}} !!Total\n|-\n|align=left|[[Basketball at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]\n|15 || 1 || 2 || 18\n|-\n|align=left|[[FIBA Basketball World Cup|FIBA World Cup]]\n|5 || 3 || 4 || 12\n|-\n|align=left|[[FIBA AmeriCup]]\n|7 || 1 || - || 8\n|-\n! Total !! 27 !! 5 !! 6 !! 38\n|}\n\n===Other awards===\n'''[[Basketball at the Pan American Games|Pan American Games]]'''\n* '''Gold medalists''' (8): [[Basketball at the 1951 Pan American Games|1951]], [[Basketball at the 1955 Pan American Games|1955]], [[Basketball at the 1959 Pan American Games|1959]], [[Basketball at the 1963 Pan American Games|1963]], [[Basketball at the 1967 Pan American Games|1967]], [[Basketball at the 1975 Pan American Games|1975]], [[Basketball at the 1979 Pan American Games|1979]], [[Basketball at the 1983 Pan American Games|1983]]\n* Silver medalists: (3): [[Basketball at the 1987 Pan American Games|1987]], [[Basketball at the 1995 Pan American Games|1995]], [[Basketball at the 1999 Pan American Games|1999]]\n* Bronze medalists (3): [[Basketball at the 1991 Pan American Games|1991]], [[Basketball at the 2011 Pan American Games \u2013 Men's tournament|2011]], [[Basketball at the 2015 Pan American Games \u2013 Men's tournament|2015]], [[Basketball at the 2019 Pan American Games \u2013 Men's tournament|2019]]\n\n'''[[Goodwill Games]]'''\n* '''Gold medalists''' (3): [[1986 Goodwill Games|1986]], [[1998 Goodwill Games|1998]], [[2001 Goodwill Games|2001]]\n* Silver medalists (1): [[1990 Goodwill Games|1990]]\n* Bronze medalists (1): [[1994 Goodwill Games|1994]]\n\n'''[[Basketball at the Summer Universiade|World University Games]]'''\n* '''Gold medalists''' (14): [[Basketball at the 1965 Summer Universiade|1965]], [[Basketball at the 1967 Summer Universiade|1967]], [[Basketball at the 1973 Summer Universiade|1973]], [[Basketball at the 1977 Summer Universiade|1977]], [[Basketball at the 1979 Summer Universiade|1979]], [[Basketball at the 1981 Summer Universiade|1981]], [[Basketball at the 1989 Summer Universiade|1989]], [[Basketball at the 1991 Summer Universiade|1991]], [[Basketball at the 1993 Summer Universiade|1993]], [[Basketball at the 1995 Summer Universiade|1995]], [[Basketball at the 1997 Summer Universiade|1997]], [[Basketball at the 1999 Summer Universiade|1999]], [[Basketball at the 2005 Summer Universiade|2005]], [[Basketball at the 2015 Summer Universiade \u2013 Men's tournament|2015]],<ref>The U.S. was represented by the [[2015\u201316 Kansas Jayhawks men's basketball team|University of Kansas]] team. USA Basketball doesn't include their results in its [https://www.usab.com/history/world-university-games-mens/mens-world-university-games-all-time-results-standings.aspx records].</ref> [[Basketball at the 2019 Summer Universiade \u2013 Men's tournament|2019]]\n* Silver medalists (4): [[Basketball at the 1970 Summer Universiade|1970]], [[Basketball at the 1985 Summer Universiade|1985]], [[Basketball at the 1987 Summer Universiade|1987]], [[Basketball at the 2017 Summer Universiade \u2013 Men's tournament|2017]]<ref>The U.S. was represented by the [[2017\u201318 Purdue Boilermakers men's basketball team|Purdue University]] team. USA Basketball doesn't include their results in its [https://www.usab.com/history/world-university-games-mens/mens-world-university-games-all-time-results-standings.aspx records].</ref>\n* Bronze medalists (3): [[Basketball at the 1983 Summer Universiade|1983]], [[Basketball at the 2001 Summer Universiade|2001]], [[Basketball at the 2009 Summer Universiade \u2013 Men|2009]]\n\n==Competitions==\n====Olympic Games====\nThe U.S. team has achieved unparalleled success in the Olympic games. While always being at a disadvantage to the Eastern Bloc countries that had used their best and most experienced professional players listed as soldiers or workers in a profession to subvert the amateur rules,<ref name=\"Tyler Benson\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/readingroom/docs/CIA-RDP80-00810A005600130009-0.pdf|title=Soviet Sports and Intelligence Activities|publisher=Central Intelligence Agency|work=[[Central Intelligence Agency]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/readingroom/docs/CIA-RDP80-00810A005800260002-1.pdf|title=Soviet Sports as an Instrument of Political Propaganda|publisher=Central Intelligence Agency|work=Central Intelligence Agency}}</ref> the U.S. team (typically composed of [[List of AAU men's basketball champions|AAU]] or [[College basketball|collegiate]] players) did surprisingly well, winning nine out of eleven Olympic tournaments they had entered before the introduction of NBA players.<ref name=\"USA Basketball\"/><ref name=\"USA Men's Olympic Team History\"/> The U.S. is the only Western country that achieved success in a team sport during the Eastern Bloc dominance. [[Canada men's national ice hockey team|Canada's]] [[Ice hockey at the Olympic Games#Men|results]] in [[ice hockey]] and Western European football teams' [[Football at the Summer Olympics#Men's results|results]] in [[association football|soccer]] significantly deteriorated after the introduction of the Eastern Bloc countries and their quasi-professional players in the late 1940s and early 1950s. In 1992, the U.S. team was represented by the NBA players for the first time and defeated its opponents by an average of 44 points en route to the gold medal against Croatia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usab.com/history/national-team-mens/games-of-the-xxvth-olympiad-1992.aspx|title=Games of the XXVth Olympiad -- 1992|publisher=USA Basketball}}</ref> The Americans have continued to dominate the Olympic tournaments ever since, excluding underachieving performance at the [[Basketball at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2004 Summer Olympics]].\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!colspan=9|[[Basketball at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games record]]\n!rowspan=2|Manager(s)\n|-\n!Year\n!Round\n!Position\n!{{Tooltip|Pld|Games played}}\n!{{Tooltip|W|Won}}\n!{{Tooltip|L|Lost}}\n!{{Tooltip|PF|Points for}}\n!{{Tooltip|PA|Points against}}\n!{{Tooltip|PD|Points difference}}\n|- style=\"background:gold\"\n|{{flagicon|Nazi Germany}} [[Basketball at the 1936 Summer Olympics|1936]]\n|'''Gold medalists'''\n|'''1st of 23'''\n|'''5'''<ref>United States' first opponent, Spain, didn't show up for a game because of the outbreak of the [[Spanish Civil War]]. Team USA was credited with a 2\u20130 win by a forfeit</ref>\n|'''5'''\n|'''0'''\n|'''154'''\n|'''69'''\n|'''+85'''\n|[[Jimmy Needles|Needles]]\n|- style=\"background:gold\"\n|{{flagicon|United Kingdom}} [[Basketball at the 1948 Summer Olympics|1948]]\n|'''Gold medalists'''\n|'''1st of 23'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''0'''\n|'''524'''\n|'''256'''\n|'''+268'''\n|[[Omar Browning|Browning]]\n|- style=\"background:gold\"\n|{{flagicon|Finland}} [[Basketball at the 1952 Summer Olympics|1952]]\n|'''Gold medalists'''\n|'''1st of 23'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''0'''\n|'''562'''\n|'''406'''\n|'''+156'''\n|[[Warren Womble|Womble]]\n|- style=\"background:gold\"\n|{{flagicon|Australia}} [[Basketball at the 1956 Summer Olympics|1956]]\n|'''Gold medalists'''\n|'''1st of 15'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''0'''\n|'''793'''\n|'''365'''\n|'''+428'''\n|[[Gerald Tucker|Tucker]]\n|- style=\"background:gold\"\n|{{flagicon|Italy}} [[Basketball at the 1960 Summer Olympics|1960]]\n|'''Gold medalists'''\n|'''1st of 16'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''0'''\n|'''815'''\n|'''476'''\n|'''+339'''\n|[[Pete Newell|Newell]]\n|- style=\"background:gold\"\n|{{flagicon|Japan}} [[Basketball at the 1964 Summer Olympics|1964]]\n|'''Gold medalists'''\n|'''1st of 16'''\n|'''9'''\n|'''9'''\n|'''0'''\n|'''704'''\n|'''434'''\n|'''+270'''\n|rowspan=2|[[Henry Iba|Iba]]\n|- style=\"background:gold\"\n|{{flagicon|Mexico}} [[Basketball at the 1968 Summer Olympics|1968]]\n|'''Gold medalists'''\n|'''1st of 16'''\n|'''9'''\n|'''9'''\n|'''0'''\n|'''739'''\n|'''505'''\n|'''+234'''\n|- style=\"background:silver\"\n|{{flagicon|West Germany}} [[Basketball at the 1972 Summer Olympics|1972]]\n|'''Silver medalists'''\n|'''2nd of 16'''\n|'''9'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''1'''\n|'''660'''\n|'''401'''\n|'''+259'''\n|Iba\n|- style=\"background:gold\"\n|{{flagicon|Canada}} [[Basketball at the 1976 Summer Olympics|1976]]\n|'''Gold medalists'''\n|'''1st of 12'''\n|'''7'''<ref>Egypt withdrew from the 1976 games due to the [[1976 Summer Olympics boycott|mass boycott]] by African nations. United States was credited with a 2\u20130 win by a forfeit</ref>\n|'''7'''\n|'''0'''\n|'''586'''\n|'''500'''\n|'''+86'''\n|[[Dean Smith|Smith]]\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Soviet Union|1955}} [[Basketball at the 1980 Summer Olympics|1980]]\n|colspan=8|''[[1980 Summer Olympics boycott|withdrew]]''\n|[[Dave Gavitt|Gavitt]]\n|- style=\"background:gold\"\n|style=\"border: 3px solid red\"|{{flagicon|United States}} [[Basketball at the 1984 Summer Olympics|1984]]\n|'''Gold medalists'''\n|'''1st of 12'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''0'''\n|'''763'''\n|'''506'''\n|'''+257'''\n|[[Bob Knight|Knight]]\n|- style=\"background:#cc9966\"\n|{{flagicon|South Korea|1984}} [[Basketball at the 1988 Summer Olympics|1988]]\n|'''Bronze medalists'''\n|'''3rd of 12'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''7'''\n|'''1'''\n|'''733'''\n|'''490'''\n|'''+243'''\n|[[John Thompson (basketball)|Thompson]]\n|- style=\"background:gold\"\n|{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Basketball at the 1992 Summer Olympics|1992]]\n|'''Gold medalists'''\n|'''1st of 12'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''0'''\n|'''938'''\n|'''588'''\n|'''+350'''\n|[[Chuck Daly|Daly]]\n|- style=\"background:gold\"\n|style=\"border: 3px solid red\"|{{flagicon|United States}} [[Basketball at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|1996]]\n|'''Gold medalists'''\n|'''1st of 12'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''0'''\n|'''816'''\n|'''562'''\n|'''+254'''\n|[[Lenny Wilkens|Wilkens]]\n|- style=\"background:gold\"\n|{{flagicon|Australia}} [[Basketball at the 2000 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2000]]\n|'''Gold medalists'''\n|'''1st of 12'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''0'''\n|'''760'''\n|'''587'''\n|'''+173'''\n|[[Rudy Tomjanovich|Tomjanovich]]\n|- style=\"background:#cc9966\"\n|{{flagicon|Greece}} [[Basketball at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2004]]\n|'''Bronze medalists'''\n|'''3rd of 12'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''5'''\n|'''3'''\n|'''705'''\n|'''668'''\n|'''+37'''\n|[[Larry Brown (basketball)|Brown]]\n|- style=\"background:gold\"\n|{{flagicon|China}} [[Basketball at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2008]]\n|'''Gold medalists'''\n|'''1st of 12'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''0'''\n|'''850'''\n|'''627'''\n|'''+223'''\n|rowspan=3|[[Mike Krzyzewski|Krzyzewski]]\n|- style=\"background:gold\"\n|{{flagicon|United Kingdom}} [[Basketball at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2012]]\n|'''Gold medalists'''\n|'''1st of 12'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''0'''\n|'''924'''\n|'''667'''\n|'''+257'''\n|- style=\"background:gold\"\n|{{flagicon|Brazil}} [[Basketball at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2016]]\n|'''Gold medalists'''\n|'''1st of 12'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''0'''\n|'''807'''\n|'''627'''\n|'''+180'''\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Japan}} [[Basketball at the 2020 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2020]]\n|colspan=8|''Qualified''\n|[[Gregg Popovich|Popovich]]\n|-\n|'''Total'''\n|'''15 titles'''\n|'''19/20'''\n|'''143'''\n|'''138'''\n|'''5'''\n|'''12833'''\n|'''8734'''\n|'''+4099'''\n|\n|}\n\n====FIBA World Cup====\nPrior to the introduction of the NBA players, the United States was usually represented by military, industrial or collegiate players. European and South American countries, meanwhile, were allowed to use their best players.<ref>https://www.usab.com/history/why-can-pros-complete-in-international-events.aspx</ref> In 1950 and 1954, AAU teams Denver Chevrolets (in 1950) and Peoria Caterpillars (1954) were the U.S. representatives,;<ref>https://www.usab.com/history/national-team-mens/first-world-championship-1950.aspx</ref><ref>https://www.usab.com/history/national-team-mens/second-world-championship-1954.aspx</ref> in 1959, the United States sent an Air Force team;<ref>https://www.usab.com/history/national-team-mens/third-world-championship-1959.aspx</ref> in 1963 and 1967, the team was composed of AAU, armed forces and college ranks;<ref>https://www.usab.com/history/national-team-mens/fourth-world-championship-1963.aspx</ref><ref>https://www.usab.com/history/national-team-mens/fifth-world-championship-1967.aspx</ref> in 1970 and 1974 (with the 1974 team being the youngest and least experienced team in history), the U.S. fielded exclusively collegians;<ref>https://www.usab.com/history/national-team-mens/sixth-world-championship-1970.aspx</ref><ref>https://www.usab.com/history/national-team-mens/seventh-world-championship-1974.aspx</ref> in 1978, an Athletes In Action (AIA) team was the American representative;<ref>https://www.usab.com/history/national-team-mens/eighth-world-championship-1978.aspx</ref> in 1982, 1986, and 1990, the team was again made up of collegiate players.<ref name=\"usab.com\">https://www.usab.com/history/national-team-mens/ninth-world-championship-1982.aspx</ref><ref name=\"usab.com\"/><ref>https://www.usab.com/history/national-team-mens/eleventh-world-championship-1990.aspx</ref> Starting with 1994 and with the exception of 1998, when the U.S. used players from the European leagues and college players,<ref>https://www.usab.com/history/national-team-mens/thirteenth-world-championship-1998.aspx</ref> the team was made up of NBA players.<ref>https://www.usab.com/mens/national-team/history.aspx</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!colspan=9|[[FIBA Basketball World Cup|FIBA World Cup record]]\n!rowspan=2|Manager(s)\n|-\n!Year\n!Round\n!Position\n!{{Tooltip|Pld|Games played}}\n!{{Tooltip|W|Won}}\n!{{Tooltip|L|Lost}}\n!{{Tooltip|PF|Points for}}\n!{{Tooltip|PA|Points against}}\n!{{Tooltip|PD|Points difference}}\n|- style=\"background:silver\"\n|{{flagicon|Argentina}} [[1950 FIBA World Championship|1950]]\n|'''Runners-up'''\n|'''2nd of 10'''\n|'''6'''\n|'''5'''\n|'''1'''\n|'''258'''\n|'''233'''\n|'''+25'''\n|[[Gordon Carpenter|Carpenter]]\n|- style=\"background:gold\"\n|{{flagicon|Brazil|1889}} [[1954 FIBA World Championship|1954]]\n|'''Champions'''\n|'''1st of 12'''\n|'''9'''\n|'''9'''\n|'''0'''\n|'''614'''\n|'''388'''\n|'''+226'''\n|[[Warren Womble|Womble]]\n|- style=\"background:silver\"\n|{{flagicon|Chile}} [[1959 FIBA World Championship|1959]]\n|'''Runners-up'''\n|'''2nd of 13'''\n|'''9'''\n|'''7'''\n|'''2'''\n|'''641'''\n|'''582'''\n|'''+59'''\n|[[Charles Bennett (basketball)|Bennett]]\n|- style=\"background:#9acdff;\"\n|{{flagicon|Brazil|1960}} [[1963 FIBA World Championship|1963]]\n|'''Fourth place'''\n|'''4th of 13'''\n|'''9'''\n|'''6'''\n|'''3'''