and veteran counterparts from Europe, U.S. players usually participated in a single Olympics (with [[Bob Kurland]], [[Bill Hougland]], and [[Burdette Haldorson]] being lone exceptions) and after winning a medal turned pro. Consequently, prior to 1992, U.S. teams were assembled from scratch every four years. After the introduction of NBA players, U.S. teams became more cohesive, and players often chose to compete in more than one Olympic tournament. \n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Player\n! Career\n! style=\"background-color:gold\" |Gold\n! style=\"background-color:silver\" |Silver\n! style=\"background-color:#cc9966\" |Bronze\n! Total (min. 2 medals)\n|-\n| '''{{sortname|Carmelo|Anthony}}'''\n| 2004\u20132016\n| [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]] [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]] [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]]\n| \n| [[File:Bronze medal.svg|16px]]\n| 4\n|-\n| {{sortname|David|Robinson}}\n| 1988\u20131996\n| [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]] [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]] \n| \n| [[File:Bronze medal.svg|16px]]\n| 3\n|-\n| {{sortname|LeBron|James}}\n| 2004\u20132012\n| [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]] [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]] \n| \n| [[File:Bronze medal.svg|16px]]\n| 3\n|-\n| {{sortname|Bob|Kurland}}\n| 1948\u20131952\n| [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]] [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]] \n| \n| \n| 2\n|-\n| {{sortname|Bill|Hougland}}\n| 1952\u20131956\n| [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]] [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]] \n| \n| \n| 2\n|-\n| {{sortname|Burdette|Haldorson}}\n| 1956\u20131960\n| [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]] [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]] \n| \n| \n| 2\n|-\n| {{sortname|Michael|Jordan}}\n| 1984, 1992\n| [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]] [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]] \n|\n|\n|2\n|- \n| {{sortname|Patrick|Ewing}}\n| 1984, 1992\n| [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]] [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]]\n| \n| \n| 2\n|-\n| {{sortname|Chris|Mullin}}\n| 1984, 1992\n| [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]] [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]] \n| \n| \n| 2\n|-\n| {{sortname|Charles|Barkley}}\n| 1992\u20131996\n| [[File:Gold medal.