84 Summer Olympics|1984]]\n|'''Gold medalists'''\n|'''1st of 12'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''0'''\n|'''763'''\n|'''506'''\n|'''+257'''\n|[[Bob Knight|Knight]]\n|- style=\"background:#cc9966\"\n|{{flagicon|South Korea|1984}} [[Basketball at the 1988 Summer Olympics|1988]]\n|'''Bronze medalists'''\n|'''3rd of 12'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''7'''\n|'''1'''\n|'''733'''\n|'''490'''\n|'''+243'''\n|[[John Thompson (basketball)|Thompson]]\n|- style=\"background:gold\"\n|{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Basketball at the 1992 Summer Olympics|1992]]\n|'''Gold medalists'''\n|'''1st of 12'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''0'''\n|'''938'''\n|'''588'''\n|'''+350'''\n|[[Chuck Daly|Daly]]\n|- style=\"background:gold\"\n|style=\"border: 3px solid red\"|{{flagicon|United States}} [[Basketball at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|1996]]\n|'''Gold medalists'''\n|'''1st of 12'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''0'''\n|'''816'''\n|'''562'''\n|'''+254'''\n|[[Lenny Wilkens|Wilkens]]\n|- style=\"background:gold\"\n|{{flagicon|Australia}} [[Basketball at the 2000 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2000]]\n|'''Gold medalists'''\n|'''1st of 12'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''0'''\n|'''760'''\n|'''587'''\n|'''+173'''\n|[[Rudy Tomjanovich|Tomjanovich]]\n|- style=\"background:#cc9966\"\n|{{flagicon|Greece}} [[Basketball at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2004]]\n|'''Bronze medalists'''\n|'''3rd of 12'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''5'''\n|'''3'''\n|'''705'''\n|'''668'''\n|'''+37'''\n|[[Larry Brown (basketball)|Brown]]\n|- style=\"background:gold\"\n|{{flagicon|China}} [[Basketball at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2008]]\n|'''Gold medalists'''\n|'''1st of 12'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''0'''\n|'''850'''\n|'''627'''\n|'''+223'''\n|rowspan=3|[[Mike Krzyzewski|Krzyzewski]]\n|- style=\"background:gold\"\n|{{flagicon|United Kingdom}} [[Basketball at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2012]]\n|'''Gold medalists'''\n|'''1st of 12'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''0'''\n|'''924'''\n|'''667'''\n|'''+257'''\n|- style=\"background:gold\"\n|{{flagicon|Brazil}} [[Basketball at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2016]]\n|'''Gold medalists'''\n|'''1st of 12'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''0'''\n|'''807'''\n|'''627'''\n|'''+180'''\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Japan}} [[Basketball at the 2020 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2020]]\n|colspan=8|''Qualified''\n|[[Gregg Popovich|Popovich]]\n|-\n|'''Total'''\n|'''15 titles'''\n|'''19/20'''\n|'''143'''\n|'''138'''\n|'''5'''\n|'''12833'''\n|'''8734'''\n|'''+4099'''\n|\n|}\n\n====FIBA World Cup====\nPrior to the introduction of the NBA players, the United States was usually represented by military, industrial or collegiate players. European and South American countries, meanwhile, were allowed to use their best players.<ref>https://www.usab.com/history/why-can-pros-complete-in-international-events.aspx</ref> In 1950 and 1954, AAU teams Denver Chevrolets (in 1950) and Peoria Caterpillars (1954) were the U.S. representatives,;<ref>https://www.usab.com/history/national-team-mens/first-world-championship-1950.aspx</ref><ref>https://www.usab.com/history/national-team-mens/second-world-championship-1954.aspx</ref> in 1959, the United States sent an Air Force team;<ref>https://www.usab.com/history/national-team-mens/third-world-championship-1959.aspx</ref> in 1963 and 1967, the team was composed of AAU, armed forces and college ranks;<ref>https://www.usab.com/history/national-team-mens/fourth-world-championship-1963.aspx</ref><ref>https://www.usab.com/history/national-team-mens/fifth-world-championship-1967.aspx</ref> in 1970 and 1974 (with the 1974 team being the youngest and least experienced team in history), the U.S. fielded exclusively collegians;<ref>https://www.usab.com/history/national-team-mens/sixth-world-championship-1970.aspx</ref><ref>https://www.usab.com/history/national-team-mens/seventh-world-championship-1974.aspx</ref> in 1978, an Athletes In Action (AIA) team was the American representative;<ref>https://www.usab.com/history/national-team-mens/eighth-world-championship-1978.aspx</ref> in 1982, 1986, and 1990, the team was again made up of collegiate players.<ref name=\"usab.com\">https://www.usab.com/history/national-team-mens/ninth-world-championship-1982.aspx</ref><ref name=\"usab.com\"/><ref>https://www.usab.com/history/national-team-mens/eleventh-world-championship-1990.aspx</ref> Starting with 1994 and with the exception of 1998, when the U.S. used players from the European leagues and college players,<ref>https://www.usab.com/history/national-team-mens/thirteenth-world-championship-1998.aspx</ref> the team was made up of NBA players.<ref>https://www.usab.com/mens/national-team/history.aspx</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!colspan=9|[[FIBA Basketball World Cup|FIBA World Cup record]]\n!rowspan=2|Manager(s)\n|-\n!Year\n!Round\n!Position\n!{{Tooltip|Pld|Games played}}\n!{{Tooltip|W|Won}}\n!{{Tooltip|L|Lost}}\n!{{Tooltip|PF|Points for}}\n!{{Tooltip|PA|Points against}}\n!{{Tooltip|PD|Points difference}}\n|- style=\"background:silver\"\n|{{flagicon|Argentina}} [[1950 FIBA World Championship|1950]]\n|'''Runners-up'''\n|'''2nd of 10'''\n|'''6'''\n|'''5'''\n|'''1'''\n|'''258'''\n|'''233'''\n|'''+25'''\n|[[Gordon Carpenter|Carpenter]]\n|- style=\"background:gold\"\n|{{flagicon|Brazil|1889}} [[1954 FIBA World Championship|1954]]\n|'''Champions'''\n|'''1st of 12'''\n|'''9'''\n|'''9'''\n|'''0'''\n|'''614'''\n|'''388'''\n|'''+226'''\n|[[Warren Womble|Womble]]\n|- style=\"background:silver\"\n|{{flagicon|Chile}} [[1959 FIBA World Championship|1959]]\n|'''Runners-up'''\n|'''2nd of 13'''\n|'''9'''\n|'''7'''\n|'''2'''\n|'''641'''\n|'''582'''\n|'''+59'''\n|[[Charles Bennett (basketball)|Bennett]]\n|- style=\"background:#9acdff;\"\n|{{flagicon|Brazil|1960}} [[1963 FIBA World Championship|1963]]\n|'''Fourth place'''\n|'''4th of 13'''\n|'''9'''\n|'''6'''\n|'''3'''\n|'''754'''\n|'''635'''\n|'''+119'''\n|[[Garland F. Pinholster|Pinholster]]\n|- style=\"background:#9acdff;\"\n|{{flagicon|Uruguay}} [[1967 FIBA World Championship|1967]]\n|'''Fourth place'''\n|'''4th of 13'''\n|'''9'''\n|'''7'''\n|'''2'''\n|'''675'''\n|'''583'''\n|'''+92'''\n|[[Hal Fischer|Fischer]]\n|- \n|{{flagicon|Yugoslavia}} [[1970 FIBA World Championship|1970]]\n|Fifth place\n|5th of 13\n|9\n|6\n|3\n|703\n|577\n| +126\n|Fischer\n|- style=\"background:#cc9966\"\n|{{flagicon|Puerto Rico|1952}} [[1974 FIBA World Championship|1974]]\n|'''Third place'''\n|'''3rd of 14'''\n|'''9'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''1'''\n|'''938'''\n|'''758'''\n|'''+180'''\n|[[Gene Bartow|Bartow]]\n|- \n|{{flagicon|Philippines|1936}} [[1978 FIBA World Championship|1978]]\n|Fifth place\n|5th of 14\n|10\n|6\n|4\n|908\n|843\n| +65\n|[[Bill Oates|Oates]]\n|- style=\"background:silver\"\n|{{flagicon|Colombia}} [[1982 FIBA World Championship|1982]]\n|'''Runners-up'''\n|'''2nd of 13'''\n|'''9'''\n|'''7'''\n|'''2'''\n|'''857'''\n|'''768'''\n|'''+89'''\n|[[Bob Weltlich|Weltlich]]\n|- style=\"background:gold\"\n|{{flagicon|Spain}} [[1986 FIBA World Championship|1986]]\n|'''Champions'''\n|'''1st of 24'''\n|'''10'''\n|'''9'''\n|'''1'''\n|'''845'''\n|'''712'''\n|'''+133'''\n|[[Lute Olson|Olson]]\n|- style=\"background:#cc9966\"\n|{{flagicon|Argentina}} [[1990 FIBA World Championship|1990]]\n|'''Third place'''\n|'''3rd of 16'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''6'''\n|'''2'''\n|'''804'''\n|'''710'''\n|'''+94'''\n|[[Mike Krzyzewski|Krzyzewski]]\n|- style=\"background:gold\"\n|{{flagicon|Canada}} [[1994 FIBA World Championship|1994]]\n|'''Champions'''\n|'''1st of 16'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''0'''\n|'''961'''\n|'''659'''\n|'''+302'''\n|[[Don Nelson|Nelson]]\n|- style=\"background:#cc9966\"\n|{{flagicon|Greece}} [[1998 FIBA World Championship|1998]]\n|'''Third place'''\n|'''3rd of 16'''\n|'''9'''\n|'''7'''\n|'''2'''\n|'''739'''\n|'''634'''\n|'''+105'''\n|[[Rudy Tomjanovich|Tomjanovich]]\n|-\n|style=\"border: 3px solid red\"|{{flagicon|United States}} [[2002 FIBA World Championship|2002]]\n|Sixth place\n|6th of 16\n|9\n|6\n|3\n|832\n|679\n| +153\n|[[George Karl|Karl]]\n|- style=\"background:#cc9966\"\n|{{flagicon|Japan}} [[2006 FIBA World Championship|2006]]\n|'''Third place'''\n|'''3rd of 24'''\n|'''9'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''1'''\n|'''932'''\n|'''748'''\n|'''+184'''\n|Krzyzewski\n|- style=\"background:gold\"\n|{{flagicon|Turkey}} [[2010 FIBA World Championship|2010]]\n|'''[[2010 FIBA World Championship Final|Champions]]'''\n|'''1st of 24'''\n|'''9'''\n|'''9'''\n|'''0'''\n|'''835'''\n|'''614'''\n|'''+221'''\n|rowspan=2|Krzyzewski\n|- style=\"background:gold\"\n|{{flagicon|Spain}} [[2014 FIBA Basketball World Cup|2014]]\n|'''[[2014 FIBA Basketball World Cup Final|Champions]]'''\n|'''1st of 24'''\n|'''9'''\n|'''9'''\n|'''0'''\n|'''941'''\n|'''644'''\n|'''+297'''\n|-\n|{{flagicon|China}} [[2019 FIBA Basketball World Cup|2019]]\n|Seventh place\n|7th of 32\n|'''9'''\n|'''6'''\n|'''2'''\n|'''692'''\n|'''587'''\n|'''+105'''\n|[[Gregg Popovich|Popovich]]\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Philippines}}{{flagicon|Japan}}{{flagicon|Indonesia}} [[2023 FIBA Basketball World Cup|2023]]\n|colspan=8|''To be determined''\n|\n|-\n|'''Total'''\n|'''5 titles'''\n|'''18/19'''\n|'''158'''\n|'''129'''\n|'''29'''\n|'''13929'''\n|'''11354'''\n|'''+1883'''\n|\n|}\n\n====FIBA AmeriCup====\nPrior to the implementation of a new FIBA competition system in 2017, the U.S. team used different players depending on the circumstances. In 1992,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usab.com/history/national-team-mens/mens-tournament-of-the-americas-1992.aspx|title=MEN'S TOURNAMENT OF THE AMERICAS -- 1992|publisher=USA Basketball}}</ref> 1999,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usab.com/history/national-team-mens/mens-tournament-of-the-americas-1999.aspx|title=MEN'S TOURNAMENT OF THE AMERICAS -- 1999|publisher=USA Basketball}}</ref> 2003<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usab.com/history/national-team-mens/mens-tournament-of-the-americas-2003.aspx|title=MEN'S TOURNAMENT OF THE AMERICAS -- 2003|publisher=USA Basketball}}</ref> and 2007,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usab.com/history/national-team-mens/mens-fiba-americas-championship-2007.aspx|title=MEN'S FIBA AMERICAS CHAMPIONSHIP 2007|publisher=USA Basketball}}</ref> the Americans sent in NBA players as they needed to qualify for the Olympics. In 1989<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usab.com/history/national-team-mens/fiba-americas-championship-1989.aspx|title=FIBA Americas Championship -- 1989|publisher=USA Basketball}}</ref> and 2005,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usab.com/history/national-team-mens/fiba-americas-championship-2005.aspx|title=FIBA Americas Championship -- 2005|publisher=USA Basketball}}</ref> the U.S. also used the tournament for qualification purposes but sent in either college players (in 1989 NBA players weren't allowed) or [[NBA G League|NBA Development League]], [[Continental Basketball Association|CBA]] and European leagues players (in 2005 the U.S. team didn't need to win gold in order to qualify for the World Championship). In 1993,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usab.com/history/national-team-mens/fiba-americas-championship-1993.aspx|title=FIBA Americas Championship -- 1993|publisher=USA Basketball}}</ref> 1997<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usab.com/history/national-team-mens/fiba-americas-championship-1997.aspx|title=FIBA Americas Championship -- 1997|publisher=USA Basketball}}</ref> and 2001,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usab.com/history/national-team-mens/fiba-americas-championship-2001.aspx|title=FIBA Americas Championship -- 2001|publisher=USA Basketball}}</ref> the U.S. team entered the tournament without any specific purpose and was represented by CBA players in 1993 and 1997, and by [[National Junior College Athletic Association|junior players]] in 2001. In 1980, 1984, 1988, 1995, 2009, 2011, 2013 and 2015, the American team didn't enter the tournament. In 2017,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usab.com/history/national-team-mens/fiba-americas-championship-2017.aspx|title=FIBA AmeriCup -- 2017|publisher=USA Basketball}}</ref> the U.S. participated for the first time in ten years with a squad of NBA G League players and American professionals playing in European leagues.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!colspan=9|[[FIBA AmeriCup|FIBA AmeriCup record]]\n!rowspan=2|Manager(s)\n|-\n!Year\n!Round\n!Position\n!{{Tooltip|Pld|Games played}}\n!{{Tooltip|W|Won}}\n!{{Tooltip|L|Lost}}\n!{{Tooltip|PF|Points for}}\n!{{Tooltip|PA|Points against}}\n!{{Tooltip|PD|Points difference}}\n|- \n|{{flagicon|Puerto Rico|1952}} [[1980 Tournament of the Americas|1980]]\n|rowspan=3 colspan=8|''Did not participate''\n|\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Brazil|1968}} [[1984 Tournament of the Americas|1984]]\n|\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Uruguay}} [[1988 Tournament of the Americas|1988]]\n|\n|- style=\"background:silver\"\n|{{flagicon|Mexico}} [[1989 Tournament of the Americas|1989]]\n|'''Runners-up'''\n|'''2nd of 12'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''6'''\n|'''2'''\n|'''776'''\n|'''740'''\n|'''+36'''\n|[[Bobby Cremins|Cremins]]\n|- style=\"background:gold\"\n|style=\"border: 3px solid red\"|{{flagicon|United States}} [[1992 Tournament of the Americas|1992]]\n|'''Champions'''\n|'''1st of 10'''\n|'''6'''\n|'''6'''\n|'''0'''\n|'''727'''\n|'''418'''\n|'''+309'''\n|[[Chuck Daly|Daly]]\n|- style=\"background:gold\"\n|{{flagicon|Puerto Rico|1952}} [[1993 Tournament of the Americas|1993]]\n|'''Champions'''\n|'''1st of 10'''\n|'''7'''\n|'''6'''\n|'''1'''\n|'''710'''\n|'''659'''\n|'''+51'''\n|[[Mike Thibault|Thibault]]\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Argentina}} [[1995 Tournament of the Americas|1995]]\n|colspan=8|''Did not participate''\n|\n|- style=\"background:gold\"\n|{{flagicon|Uruguay}} [[1997 Tournament of the Americas|1997]]\n|'''Champions'''\n|'''1st of 10'''\n|'''9'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''1'''\n|'''845'''\n|'''759'''\n|'''+86'''\n|[[Morris McHone|McHone]]\n|- style=\"background:gold\"\n|{{flagicon|Puerto Rico}} [[1999 Tournament of the Americas|1999]]\n|'''Champions'''\n|'''1st of 10'''\n|'''10'''\n|'''10'''\n|'''0'''\n|'''978'''\n|'''662'''\n|'''+316'''\n|[[Larry Brown (basketball)|Brown]]\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Argentina}} [[2001 Tournament of the Americas|2001]]\n|colspan=8|''Did not participate''{{ref label|N|N|Nb}}\n|\n|- style=\"background:gold\"\n|{{flagicon|Puerto Rico}} [[2003 Tournament of the Americas|2003]]\n|'''Champions'''\n|'''1st of 10'''\n|'''10'''\n|'''10'''\n|'''0'''\n|'''1017'''\n|'''708'''\n|'''+309'''\n|Brown\n|- style=\"background:#9acdff;\"\n|{{flagicon|Dominican Republic}} [[2005 FIBA Americas Championship|2005]]\n|'''Fourth place'''\n|'''4th of 10'''\n|'''10'''\n|'''4'''\n|'''6'''\n|'''846'''\n|'''850'''\n|'''\u22124'''\n|McHone\n|- style=\"background:gold\"\n|style=\"border: 3px solid red\"|{{flagicon|United States}} [[2007 FIBA Americas Championship|2007]]\n|'''Champions'''\n|'''1st of 10'''\n|'''10'''\n|'''10'''\n|'''0'''\n|'''1167'''\n|'''772'''\n|'''+395'''\n|[[Mike Krzyzewski|Krzyzewski]]\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Puerto Rico}} [[2009 FIBA Americas Championship|2009]]\n|rowspan=4 colspan=8|''Did not participate''\n|\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Argentina}} [[2011 FIBA Americas Championship|2011]]\n|\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Venezuela}} [[2013 FIBA Americas Championship|2013]]\n|\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Mexico}} [[2015 FIBA Americas Championship|2015]]\n|\n|- style=\"background:gold\"\n|{{flagicon|Argentina}}{{flagicon|Colombia}}{{flagicon|Uruguay}} [[2017 FIBA AmeriCup|2017]]\n|'''Champions'''\n|'''1st of 12'''\n|'''5'''\n|'''5'''\n|'''0'''\n|'''414'''\n|'''316'''\n|'''+98'''\n|[[Jeff Van Gundy|Van Gundy]]\n|-\n|'''Total'''\n|'''7 titles'''\n|'''9/18'''\n|'''75'''\n|'''65'''\n|'''10'''\n|'''7480'''\n|'''5884'''\n|'''+1596'''\n|\n|}\n\n==Team==\n===Current roster===\n{{see also|2019 United States FIBA Basketball World Cup team}}\n{{2019 United States FIBA Basketball World Cup team roster}}\n\n===Medal leaders===\n====Olympic====\nUntil 1992, there were few players who got the opportunity to compete in multiple Olympics. Unlike their seasoned and veteran counterparts from Europe, U.S. players usually participated in a single Olympics (with [[Bob Kurland]], [[Bill Hougland]], and [[Burdette Haldorson]] being lone exceptions) and after winning a medal turned pro. Consequently, prior to 1992, U.S. teams were assembled from scratch every four years. After the introduction of NBA players, U.S. teams became more cohesive, and players often chose to compete in more than one Olympic tournament. \n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Player\n! Career\n! style=\"background-color:gold\" |Gold\n! style=\"background-color:silver\" |Silver\n! style=\"background-color:#cc9966\" |Bronze\n! Total (min. 2 medals)\n|-\n| '''{{sortname|Carmelo|Anthony}}'''\n| 2004\u20132016\n| [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]] [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]] [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]]\n| \n| [[File:Bronze medal.svg|16px]]\n| 4\n|-\n| {{sortname|David|Robinson}}\n| 1988\u20131996\n| [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]] [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]] \n| \n| [[File:Bronze medal.svg|16px]]\n| 3\n|-\n| {{sortname|LeBron|James}}\n| 2004\u20132012\n| [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]] [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]] \n| \n| [[File:Bronze medal.svg|16px]]\n| 3\n|-\n| {{sortname|Bob|Kurland}}\n| 1948\u20131952\n| [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]] [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]] \n| \n| \n| 2\n|-\n| {{sortname|Bill|Hougland}}\n| 1952\u20131956\n| [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]] [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]] \n| \n| \n| 2\n|-\n| {{sortname|Burdette|Haldorson}}\n| 1956\u20131960\n| [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]] [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]] \n| \n| \n| 2\n|-\n| {{sortname|Michael|Jordan}}\n| 1984, 1992\n| [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]] [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]] \n|\n|\n|2\n|- \n| {{sortname|Patrick|Ewing}}\n| 1984, 1992\n| [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]] [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]]\n| \n| \n| 2\n|-\n| {{sortname|Chris|Mullin}}\n| 1984, 1992\n| [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]] [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]] \n| \n| \n| 2\n|-\n| {{sortname|Charles|Barkley}}\n| 1992\u20131996\n| [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]] [[File:Gold medal.svg|16px]] \n| \n| \n| 2\n|-\n| {{sortname|Scottie|Pippen}}\n|