{"title_page": "Theobald Dillon, 1st Viscount Dillon", "text_new": "{{Short description|17th-century Irish viscount}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Theobald Dillon, 1st Viscount Dillon\n| image         =\n| alt           =\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = c. 1530\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = 1624\n| death_place   = Kilfaughny, [[County Westmeath]]\n| nationality   = Irish\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Landowner\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = Sharp practices with indigenous freeholders\n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n[[File:DillonArms.jpg|thumb|200px|Arms of Dillon: ''Argent, a lion passant between three crescents gules'']]\n\n'''Theobald Dillon, 1st Viscount Dillon''' (died 1624), was an Irish military commander and adventurer. He held extensive lands in eastern [[Connacht]] and north-western [[Leinster]], some acquired by sharp practices. He was a loyal supporter of [[Elizabeth I of England]] in her Irish wars.\n\n==Birth and origins==\nTheobald was born very approximately around 1530,{{efn|name=YearB}} probably at Ballynakill, the habitual home of his father and grandfather. He was the third son of Thomas Dillon{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/177/ 177, line 14]|ps=: \"... [the 1st Viscount was] the third son of Thomas Dillon, son of James ...\"}} and his wife Margery Dillon, also called Mary.{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/174/ 174, line 7]|ps=: \"Thomas, the eldest son ... married Margery, daughter of Christopher Dillon, of Kilmore ...\"}}{{sfn|Cokayne|1916|p=[https://archive.org/details/completepeerageo04coka/page/357/ 357, line 16]|ps=: \"THEOBALD DILLON, 3rd s. of Thomas D. of Ballynakill, by Mary, da. of Christopher Dillon, of Kilmore ...\"}} His father was the eldest son of his grandfather James Dillon, nicknamed ''the Prior'',{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/173/ 173, line 24]|ps=: \"... he [James Dillon] obtained a temporary lease of divers Monasteries ... he was nicknamed ''the Prior'' ...\"}} because he took care of several monastic properties at the dissolution of the monasteries. His father's side of the family descended from Lord Dillon of [[Drumraney]], [[County Westmeath]]. Theobald's mother was a daughter of Christopher Dillon of Kilmore.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTELodge1789[httpsarchiveorgdetailspeerageofireland04lodgpage174 174, line 7]\"/> His father's family as his mother's family were branches of the same widespread [[Normans in Ireland|Old English]] family that descends from Sir Henry Dillon who came to Ireland with [[John, King of England|Prince John]] in 1185.{{sfn|Webb|1878|p=[https://archive.org/details/acompendiumiris00webbgoog/page/n157/ 149, line 7]|ps=: \"... [Sir Henry Dillon] came to Ireland in 1185 as secretary to Prince John ...\"}}\n\nTheobald appears below among his brothers as the third son: \n#Gerald;{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/174/ 174, line 14]|ps=: \"Gerald, who married Cicely ...\"}}\n#Edmund;{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/174/ 174, line 23]|ps=: \"Edmund, who settled in the castle of Ardnegragh, in county of Westmeath ...\"}}\n#''' Theobald''' (died 1624), the subject of this article;\n#Garret, a captain of an independent troop, ancestor of [[Garrett Dillon]], [[Recorder of Dublin]].{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/175/ 175, line 22]|ps=: \"Garret, who was Captain of an independent company in the reign of Q. Elizabeth ...\"}} and\n#James, from whom descend the Dillons of Ballynakill and some other Dillon cadet branches.{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/177/ 177, line 7]|ps=: \"James, the fifth and youngest son of Thomas, was father of James who lived in the reign of James I. and was seated at Carrownegarry, in county Roscommon; ... from this branch descended the families of Ballynakill, Tully, Portmore, Rathmoyle, Cloontowart ...\"}}\n\nTheobald had three sisters:\n#Rose, who married Thomas Dillon, son and successor to Gerald of Drumrany;{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/174/ 174, line 10]|ps=: \"Rose, married to Thomas Dillon, son and successor to Gerald, of Drumrany ...\"}}\n#Catherine, who married Edmund Fitz-Edmund Dillon of Kilcomane;{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/174 174, line 11]|ps=: \"Catherine, to Edmund Fitz-Edmund Dillon of Kilcomane;\"}} and\n#Bridget, who married a Dalton of Moyvannane.{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/174/ 174, line 12]|ps=: \"Bridget, to ___ Dalton of Moyvannane.\"}}\n\n<div style=\"float: right; margin: 0 0 0 1em\">\n{{chart top|width=auto|collapsed=no|Family tree}}\n{{chart/start|style=clear: both; font-size: 80%; width: 40em;}}\n{{chart|Txt|Txt=Theobald Dillon with wife, parents, and other selected relatives.|boxstyle_Txt=border: 0 solid white; padding-bottom: 1em; text-align: left;}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart/start|style=font-size: 70%;}}\n{{chart|GrdDl|y|Ismay|boxstyle=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em;\n |GrdDl='''Gerald<br>Dillon of<br>Dunimoney'''\n |Ismay='''Ismay<br>Tuite}}\n{{chart| | | |)|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|.}}\n{{chart| | | Rbt | |JmsDl|y|CthDn| | Wlm |boxstyle=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em;\n |Rbt='''Robert<br>Dillon'''<br>{{midsize|of Dunimoney}}\n |JmsDl='''James<br>Dillon'''<br>{{midsize|The Prior}}\n |CthDn='''Catherine<br>Dalton'''\n |Wlm='''William<br>Dillon'''}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | |!}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | |ThsDl|y|Mrgry|boxstyle=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em;\n |ThsDl='''Thomas<br>Dillon'''\n |Mrgry='''Margery<br>Dillon'''}}\n{{chart| |,|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|v|-|^|-|-|-|-|-|v}}\n{{chart|Gerld| |Edmnd| |ThbD1|y|Elnor| |Garrt|boxstyle=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em;\n |Gerld='''Gerald<br>Dillon'''\n |Edmnd='''Edmund<br>Dillon'''\n |ThbD1=[[Theobald Dillon, 1st Viscount Dillon|Theobald<br>'''1st<br>Viscount''']]<br>{{midsize|d. 1624}}|boxstyle_ThbD1=border: 2px solid red; border-radius: 0.5em; background: lavender;\n |Elnor='''Eleanor<br>Tuite'''<br>{{midsize|d. 1638}}\n |Garrt='''Garret<br>Dillon'''<br>{{midsize|Captain}}}}\n{{chart| |,|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|v|-|^|-|-|-|-|-|v| }}\n{{chart|Chrst|y|Janet| |Lucas|y|JaneM| |JmsDl|boxstyle=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em;\n |Chrst='''Christopher<br>Dillon of<br>Ballylaghan'''<br>{{midsize|d. 1624}}\n |Janet='''Janet<br>Dillon'''<br>{{midsize|m. 1604}}\n |Lucas='''Lucas<br>Dillon of<br>Loughglynn'''\n |JaneM='''Jane<br>Moore'''\n |JmsDl=[[James Dillon (officer)|'''James<br>Dillon''']]<br>{{midsize|c. 1600 \u2013<br>aft. 1669}}}}\n{{chart| |,|-|^|-|v|-|-|-|.| |`|-|.}}\n{{chart|LcsD2| |ThsD4| |ThbDl| |RbtDl|y| Ros |boxstyle=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em;\n |LcsD2=Lucas<br>'''2nd<br>Viscount'''<br>{{midsize|1610\u20131629}}|boxstyle_LcsD2=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em; background: lavender;\n |ThsD4=[[Thomas Dillon, 4th Viscount Dillon|Thomas<br>'''4th<br>Viscount''']]<br>{{midsize|1615\u20131673}}|boxstyle_ThsD4=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em; background: lavender;\n |ThbDl='''Theobald<br>Dillon'''\n |RbtDl='''Robert<br>Dillon<br>of<br>Loughglynn'''<br>{{midsize|d. 1691}}\n |Ros='''Rose<br>Dillon<br>of<br>Streams-<br>town'''}}\n{{chart| |!| | | |!| | | |!| | | |,|-|'| | | }}\n{{chart|ThbD3| |ThsD5| |LcsD6| |ThbD7|y| Mry |boxstyle=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em;\n |ThbD3=Theobald<br>'''3rd<br>Viscount'''<br>{{midsize|1629\u20131630}}|boxstyle_ThbD3=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em; background: lavender;\n |ThsD5=Thomas<br>'''5th<br>Viscount'''<br>{{midsize|d. 1674}}|boxstyle_ThsD5=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em; background: lavender;\n |LcsD6=[[Lucas Dillon, 6th Viscount Dillon|Lucas<br>'''6th<br>Viscount''']]<br>{{midsize|d. 1682}}|boxstyle_LcsD6=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em; background: lavender;\n |ThbD7=[[Theobald Dillon, 7th Viscount Dillon|Theobald<br>'''7th<br>Viscount''']]<br>{{midsize|d. 1691<br>Jacobite}}|boxstyle_ThbD7=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em; background: lavender;\n |Mry='''Mary<br>Talbot'''<br>{{midsize|d. 1691}}}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart/start|style=clear: both;}}\n{{chart|Leg|Leg='''Legend'''|boxstyle_Leg=border: 0 solid white;}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart/start|style=clear: both; font-size: 70%;}}\n{{chart|SbjBx|SbjTx| |Bk1Bx|Bk1Tx|\n |SbjBx=XXX|boxstyle_SbjBx=border: 2px solid red; border-radius: 0.5em; color: white;\n |SbjTx=Theobald<br>Dillon|boxstyle_SbjTx=border: 0 solid white; text-align: left;\n |Bk1Bx=XXX|boxstyle_Bk1Bx=background: lavender; border-radius: 0.5em; border-width: 1px; color: lavender;\n |Bk1Tx=[[Viscount Dillon|Viscounts<br>Dillon]]|boxstyle_Bk1Tx=border: 0 solid white; text-align: left;}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart/start|style=clear: both; font-size: 80%; width: 40em;}}\n{{chart|Txt|Txt=Also see the lists of siblings and children in the text.|boxstyle_Txt=border: 0 solid white; text-align: left;}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart_bottom}}\n</div>\n\nIn 1559 Theobald commanded an independent force.{{sfn|Webb|1878|p=[https://archive.org/details/acompendiumiris00webbgoog/page/n157/ 149]|ps=: \"In 1559 he commanded an independent troop in the royal cause ...\"}}\n\n==Marriage and children==\nTheobald Dillon married Eleanor Tuite. So far the sources agree. However, she is either the widow or the daughter of William Tuite according to sources.{{sfn|Burke|1832|p=[https://archive.org/details/ageneralandhera01burkgoog/page/n422 367, left column, line 4]|ps=: \"His lordship [Theobald Dillon] m. Eleanora, daughter of Sir Edward Tuite, knt., of Tuitestown, in the county of Westmeath, and widow of William Tuite of Monilea ...\"}}{{sfn|Cokayne|1916|p=[https://archive.org/details/completepeerageo04coka/page/357/ 357, line 25]|ps=: \"He [Theobald Dillon] m. Eleanor, da. of William Tuite of Tuitestown, co. Westmeath.\"}}\n\nThey had 19 children, eight sons and 11 daughters,{{sfn|Debrett|1828|p=[https://archive.org/details/debrettspeerage01debrgoog/page/n326/ 748, line 11]|ps=: \"He [Theobald Dillon] had issue 8 sons and 11 das.;\"}}\n\nThe eight sons were:{{efn|Burke (1949) mentions only Christopher and Lucas; Cokayne (1916) does not mention his children; Debrett states he had eight sons but does not give details. Lodge lists all eight sons in detail.}}\n#Christopher (died 28 February 1624), who was the eldest and married the eldest daughter of [[James Dillon, 1st Earl of Roscommon]] and became the father of the 2nd Viscount and the 4th Viscount;{{sfn|Burke|1832|p=[https://archive.org/details/ageneralandhera01burkgoog/page/n422/ 367, left column, line 9]|ps=: \"CHRISTOPHER (Sir), of Bealalahin, in the county of Mayo, who m. in 1604, Lady Jane Dillon, eldest daughter of James, first Earl of Roscommon, and dying before his father, left seven sons and five daughters.\"}}{{sfn|Cokayne|1916|p=[https://archive.org/details/completepeerageo04coka/page/357/ 357, line 33]|ps=: \"Christopher was s. and h. ap. of the last Viscount but d. v.p., 28 Feb 1623/4.\"}}\n#Lucas, ancestor of the 7th and later viscounts;{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/181/ 181, line 2]|ps=: \"Sir Lucas, from whom the present Lord Dillon descends.\"}}\n#William, styled of Tolchan;{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/181/ 181, line 4]|ps=: \"William Dillon of Tolchan, Esq; who had considerable estates assigned to him.\"}}\n#Thomas, styled of Brackloon;{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/181/ 181, line 10]|ps=: \"Thomas, on whom the estates of his nephew George devolved he was born in the Tower of London, and styled of Bracklyn or Brackloon in county of Roscomon.\"}}\n#Edward, who became a Franciscan monk;{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/182/ 182, line 38]|ps=: \"Edward and George, Friars of the Order of St. Francis.}}\n#George, who became a Franciscan monk;<ref name=\"FOOTNOTELodge1789[httpsarchiveorgdetailspeerageofireland04lodgpage182 182, line 38]\"/>\n#John, who became an officer in the army and died unmarried;{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/182/ 182, line 40]|ps=: \"John, who had a command in the army, and died unmarried}}\n#[[James Dillon (officer)|James]] (c. 1600 \u2013 1669), who was the 8th and youngest son;{{sfn|Murtagh|2004|p=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_0198613660/page/210/ 210, right column]|ps=: \"... army officer, was probably born at Kilfaughny, co. Westmeath, the eighth and youngest son of nineteen children of Theobald, first Viscount Dillon ... \"}}\n\nThe eleven daughters were:\n#Rose, who died young; {{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/184/ 184, line 12]|ps=: \"Daughter Rose, who died young.\"}}\n#Margaret, who married Robert Dillon of Cannestown;{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/184/ 184, line 13]|ps=: \"Margaret, married Robert Dillon of Cannestown in Westmeath&nbsp;...\"}} \n#Anne, who was the mother of [[Theobald Taaffe, 1st Earl of Carlingford]];{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/184/ 184, line 19]|ps=: \"Anne to John, Viscount Taaffe of Corran, and mother of Theobald, Earl of Carlingford.\"}}\n#Katherine, who married Sir Ulick Burke of [[Glinsk Castle|Glinsk]], 1st Baronet;{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/184/ 184, line 21]|ps=: \"Catherine to Sir Ulick Bourke of Glinsk in the county of Roscomon, Bart.\"}}\n#Mary, who married Gerald Pettyt of [[Mullingar]] in County Westmeath;{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/184/ 184, line 23]|ps=: \"Mary, to Gerald Pettyt of Irishtown or Molyngar in Westmeath&nbsp;...\"}}\n#Elizabeth, to Thomas Fitzgerald of Newcastle in County Longford;{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/184/ 184, line 30]|ps=: \"Elizabeth,  to Thomas Fitzgerald of Newcastle, in county of Longford&nbsp;...\"}}\n#Jane, who married Hugh O'Conor of Castlereagh.{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/184/ 184, line 36]|ps=: \"Jane to Hugh O'Connor Dunn of Castlereagh in Roscommon ...\"}}\n#Ellen (died 1629), who became a nun with the [[Poor Clares]];{{sfn|Clarke|2004|p=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_0198613660/page/203/ 203, left column, line 20]|ps= \"Having arrived in Dublin on 13 June 1629, they established themselves in Merchant's Quay. As her sister Eleanor died soon after her return to Ireland, it was Cecily Dillon who was elected abbess&nbsp;...\"}}{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/184/ 184, line 38]|ps=: \"Ellen, Cecilia, Nuns of the Order of St. Clare, and who established the Franciscan order of nuns in Galway.\"}}\n#[[Cecily Dillon|Cecily]] (c. 1603 \u2013 1653), who became the first Abbess of the Poor Clares in Ireland;<ref name=\"FOOTNOTELodge1789[httpsarchiveorgdetailspeerageofireland04lodgpage184 184, line 38]\"/>{{sfn|Chambers|1882|p=[https://archive.org/details/TheLifeOfMaryWardV1/page/n266/ 198, line 16]|ps=: \"In the year 1625 six nuns left the Gravelines convent for that country [Ireland] ... Two of them were daughters of Viscount Dillon ... Mary Joseph and Cicely Francis.\"}}{{sfn|Clarke|2004|p=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_0198613660/page/202/ 202]|ps= \"Dillon, Cecily (c 1603 \u2013 1653). Poor Clare abbess&nbsp;...\"}}\n#Bridget, who died unmarried; and {{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/184/ 184, line 41]|ps=: \"Bridget, and Barbara, died unmarried.\"}}\n#Barbara, who died unmarried.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTELodge1789[httpsarchiveorgdetailspeerageofireland04lodgpage184 184, line 41]\"/>\n\n==Later life==\nIn 1582 in the context of the [[Composition of Connacht]], a [[surrender and regrant]] action, Dillon was appointed collector-general of the composition money in Connacht and [[Thomond]].{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/177 177, line 18]|ps=: \"... was appointed by patent, General Collector and Receiver of all and singular the Composition Money, within the provinces of Connaught and Thomond.\"}} During this period of the English reconquest in Connacht, Dillon was involved in some sharp practices with the local landholders. In particular he persuaded the various [[Costello (surname)|Costello]] freeholders of the [[Barony of Costello]] in eastern [[County Mayo]], to save expense and ensure the smooth legal transfer, to allow him to surrender their lands for them in one land-title in the [[Surrender and regrant]] process and had it regranted in his own name, becoming the legal landowner in the process. He never returned this title to the lands to the native owners, which would lead to [[rapparee]] actions by [[Dubhaltach Caoch Mac Coisdealbhaigh|Dudley Costello]] (or Costellogh) against the Dillons in the 1760s.{{sfn|Moody|Martin|Byrne|2009|p=[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=5zov9-tSFCoC&pg=PA448 448, line 27]|ps=: \"Dudley Costello, the most celebrated of the Connacht tories, was an 'ensignman' whose estate was held by Lord Dillon, against whom he conducted a vigorous private war.\"}}\n\nHe fought under [[Robert Devereux, 2nd Earl of Essex|the Earl of Essex]] in the [[Nine Years' War (Ireland)|Nine Years' War]] (1593\u20131603) and was knighted by him on 24 July 1599.{{sfn|Cokayne|1916|p=[https://archive.org/details/completepeerageo04coka/page/357/ 357, line 21]|ps=: \"... took an active part against the rebel Irish under Tyrone, 1598\u20131601; knighted by the Earl of Essex, 24 July 1599.\"}}{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/177/ 177, line 31]|ps=: \" ... and in 1559, received the honour of Knighthood in the field of battle.\"}}{{efn|Lodge give this year as 1559, which seems to be an error.}} To put this into perspective it should be said that Theobald was already in his sixties and that Essex knighted a great many people and was mocked by saying \"he never drew sword but to make knights\".{{sfn|Hammer|2004|p=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_0198613652/page/957/ 957, left column]|ps=: \"Already angry over the vast cost of his expedition, she was further enraged by Essex's profligacy in bestowing knighthoods ...\"}}\n\nOn 19 July 1608, [[King James I of England|King James I]] gave him a patent confirming the possession of the manor and town of Kilfaughny in County Westmeath{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/178/ 178, line 19]|ps=: \"The King also ... did by patent 19 July 1608, 6 of his reign, regrant, sell, and confirm to him, his heirs and assignes forever, the entire manor, castle, or stone-fort and town of Killenfaghny ... \"}} where he then lived and finally died.\n\nOn 16 March 1622, [[James I of England|King James I]] created him Viscount Dillon of Costello-Gallen, cementing his legal title. He became the first of a long succession of [[Viscounts Dillon|viscounts Dillon]]. [[Gallen (barony)|Gallen]] and [[Costello (barony)|Costello]] form the title's territorial designation. They are baronies of County Mayo.{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/177/ 177, line 35]|ps=: \"... creating him Viscount Dillon of Costello-Gallen in the Kingdom of Ireland, by letters patent bearing date at Westminster, 16 March 1621-2 ...\"}}\n\nLord Dillon, as he now was, held the title of [[Lord President of Connaught]] from c. 1621 on, which he shared with [[Charles Wilmot, 1st Viscount Wilmot|Charles Wilmot]] from 1616\u20131644.{{sfn|Pollard|1900|p=[https://archive.org/details/dictionarynatio13stepgoog/page/n72 60, left column]|ps=: \"On 3 June 1616 he [Charles Wilmot] was appointed president of Connaught.\"}}\n\n==Death and succession==\nLord Dillon died on 15 March 1624{{sfn|Debrett|1828|p=[https://archive.org/details/debrettspeerage01debrgoog/page/n326/ 748, line 9]|ps=: \"... and d. 15 March 1624 ...\"}} in Kilfaughny in County Westmeath. It is said that he died \"at so advanced an age, that at one time he had the satisfaction of seeing above an hundred of his descendants in his house of Killenfaghny.\"{{sfn|Webb|1878|p=[https://archive.org/details/acompendiumiris00webbgoog/page/n157/ 149, right column, line 38]|ps=Cited in the text}} Christopher, his eldest son, died on 28 February<ref name=\"FOOTNOTECokayne1916[httpsarchiveorgdetailscompletepeerageo04cokapage357 357, line 33]\"/> about two weeks before his father and therefore never succeeded his father. On the first Viscount's death, the title therefore passed to his grandson Lucas, Christopher's eldest son.{{sfn|Burke|1832|p=[https://archive.org/details/ageneralandhera01burkgoog/page/n422/ 367, left column, line 26]|ps=: \"He [the 1st Viscount] was s. by his grandson LUCAS, second viscount ...\"}}\n\n{| {{Table|hide}}\n!colspan=3|Timeline\n|-\n|colspan=3|''As the birth date is uncertain, so are the ages.''\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Age!!align=\"left\"|Date!!align=\"left\"|Event\n|-\n|0||1530, about||Born.{{efn|name=YearB}}\n|-\n|29||1559||Commanded an independent force.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEWebb1878[httpsarchiveorgdetailsacompendiumiris00webbgoogpagen157 149]\"/>\n|-\n|52||1582||Made collector-general of the composition money.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTELodge1789[httpsarchiveorgdetailspeerageofireland04lodgpage177 177, line 18]\"/>\n|-\n|69||1599, 24 Jul||Knighted by [[Robert Devereux, 2nd Earl of Essex|Essex]].<ref name=\"FOOTNOTECokayne1916[httpsarchiveorgdetailscompletepeerageo04cokapage357 357, line 21]\"/>\n|-\n|78||1608, 19 Jul||[[King James I of England|James I]] gave him a patent for Kilfaughny house.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTELodge1789[httpsarchiveorgdetailspeerageofireland04lodgpage178 178, line 19]\"/>\n|-\n|91||1622, 16 Mar||Created Viscount Dillon of Costello-Gallen.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTELodge1789[httpsarchiveorgdetailspeerageofireland04lodgpage177 177, line 35]\"/>\n|-\n|93||1624, 28 Feb||His eldest son, Christopher, died.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTECokayne1916[httpsarchiveorgdetailscompletepeerageo04cokapage357 357, line 33]\"/>\n|-\n|93||1624, 15 Mar||He died and was succeeded by his grandson [[Lucas Dillon, 2nd Viscount Dillon|Lucas]].<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEDebrett1828[httpsarchiveorgdetailsdebrettspeerage01debrgoogpagen326 748, line 9]\"/>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Viscount Dillon]]\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{Notelist|refs=\n:{{efn|name=YearB|Theobald's year of birth is set at very roughly 1530 as he died in 1624 at an very advanced age, which is interpreted to mean that he was in his 90s.}}\n}}\n{{Reflist}}\n*{{citation|last=Burke |first=John |author-link=John Burke (genealogist) |date=1832 |title=A General and Heraldic Dictionary of the Peerage and Baronetage of the British Empire |edition=4th |volume=1 |publisher=Henry Colburn and Richard Bentley |publication-place=London |url=https://archive.org/details/ageneralandhera01burkgoog/}} \u2013 Abdy to Hutchinson\n*{{citation|last=Chambers |first=Mary Catherine Elizabeth |date=1882 |title=The Life of Mary Ward (1585\u20131645) |volume=1 |publisher=Burns and Oates |publication-place=London |url=https://archive.org/details/TheLifeOfMaryWardV1/}}\n*{{citation|last=Clarke |first=Frances |editor-last=Matthew |editor-first=Colin |editor-link=Colin Matthew |editor2-last=Harrison |editor2-first=Brian |editor2-link=Brian Harrison (historian) |date=2004 |title=Dillon, Cecily (c. 1603 \u2013 1653 ) |encyclopedia=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography |volume=16 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |publication-place=New York |pages=202\u2013203 |isbn=0-19-8613660 |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_0198613660/page/202/ |url-access=registration}}\n*{{citation|last=Cokayne |first=George Edward |author-link=George Edward Cokayne |editor-last=Gibbs |editor-first=Vicary |editor-link=Vicary Gibbs (St Albans MP) |date=1916 |title=The complete peerage of England, Scotland, Ireland, Great Britain and the United Kingdom, extant, extinct, or dormant |edition=2nd |volume=4 |publisher=St Catherine Press |publication-place=London |url=https://archive.org/details/completepeerageo04coka/}} - DACRE to DYSART (for Dillon)\n*{{citation|last=Debrett |first=John |author-link=John Debrett |date=1828 |title=Peerage of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland |edition=17th |volume=2 |publisher=F. C. and J. Rivington |publication-place=London |url=https://archive.org/details/debrettspeerage01debrgoog/}} - Scotland and Ireland\n*{{citation|last=Hammer |first=Paul E. J. |editor-last=Matthew |editor-first=Colin |editor-link=Colin Matthew |editor2-last=Harrison |editor2-first=Brian |editor2-link=Brian Harrison (historian) |date=2004 |title=Devereux, Robert, second earl of Essex (1565\u20131601) |encyclopedia=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography |volume=15 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |publication-place=New York |pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_0198613652/page/945/ 945\u2013960] |isbn=0-19-861365-2 |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_0198613652/ |url-access=registration}}\n*{{citation|last=Lodge |first=John |author-link=John Lodge (archivist) |date=1789 |title=The Peerage of Ireland |volume=4 |publisher=James Moore |publication-place=Dublin |url=https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/}} - Viscounts\n*{{citation|last=Moody |first=Theodore William |author-link=Theodore William Moody |last2=Martin |first2=Francis Xavier |author2-link=F. X. Martin |last3=Byrne |first3=F. J. |date=2009 |title=A New History of Ireland |volume=3 Early Modern Ireland 1534\u20131691 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |publication-place=Oxford |isbn=978-0-19-956252-7 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=5zov9-tSFCoC}}\n*{{citation|last=Murtagh |first=Harman |editor-last=Matthew |editor-first=Colin |editor-link=Colin Matthew |editor2-last=Harrison |editor2-first=Brian |editor2-link=Brian Harrison (historian) |date=2004 |title=Dillon, Sir James |encyclopedia=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography |volume=16 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |publication-place=New York |pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_0198613660/page/210/ 210\u2013211] |isbn=0-19-8613660 |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_0198613660/}}\n*{{citation|last=Pollard |first=Albert Frederick |author-link=Albert Pollard |editor-last=Lee |editor-first=Sidney |editor-link=Sidney Lee |date=1900 |title=WILMOT, SIR CHARLES, first Viscount of Athlone (d. 1633) |encyclopedia=Dictionary of National Biography |volume=62 |publisher=The Macmillan Company |publication-place=New York |pages=[https://archive.org/details/dictionarynatio13stepgoog/page/n70/ 59\u201361] |url=https://archive.org/details/dictionarynatio13stepgoog/}}\n*{{citation|last=Webb |first=Alfred |date=1878 |title=Dillon, Theobald, Viscount |dictionary=Compendium of Irish Biography |publisher=M. H. Gill & Son |publication-place=Dublin |page=[https://archive.org/details/acompendiumiris00webbgoog/page/n157/ 149] |url=https://archive.org/details/acompendiumiris00webbgoog/}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.thepeerage.com/p18959.htm#i189590 Genealogy of Theobald Dillon, 1st Viscount Dillon of Costello-Gallin on The Peerage website]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-reg|ie}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Viscount Dillon]] | years=1622&ndash;1624 | before=First Creation | after=Lucas Dillon}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dillon, Theobald Dillon, 1st Viscount}}\n[[Category:1624 deaths]]\n[[Category:16th-century births]]\n[[Category:16th-century Irish people]]\n[[Category:17th-century Irish people]]\n[[Category:Irish people of French descent]]\n[[Category:Irish soldiers]]\n[[Category:People from County Westmeath]]\n[[Category:People of the Tudor period]]\n[[Category:People of Elizabethan Ireland]]\n[[Category:Viscounts Dillon]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|17th-century Irish viscount}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Theobald Dillon, 1st Viscount Dillon\n| image         =\n| alt           =\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = c. 1530\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = 1624\n| death_place   = Kilfaughny, [[County Westmeath]]\n| nationality   = Irish\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Landowner\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = Sharp practices with indigenous freeholders\n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n[[File:DillonArms.jpg|thumb|200px|Arms of Dillon: ''Argent, a lion passant between three crescents gules'']]\n\n'''Theobald Dillon, 1st Viscount Dillon''' (died 1624), was an Irish military commander and adventurer. He held extensive lands in eastern [[Connacht]] and north-western [[Leinster]], some acquired by sharp practices. He was a loyal supporter of [[Elizabeth I of England]] in her Irish wars.\n\n==Birth and origins==\nTheobald was born very approximately around 1530,{{efn|name=YearB}} probably at Ballynakill, the habitual home of his father and grandfather. He was the third son of Thomas Dillon{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/177/ 177, line 14]|ps=: \"... [the 1st Viscount was] the third son of Thomas Dillon, son of James ...\"}} and his wife Margery Dillon, also called Mary.{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/174/ 174, line 7]|ps=: \"Thomas, the eldest son ... married Margery, daughter of Christopher Dillon, of Kilmore ...\"}}{{sfn|Cokayne|1916|p=[https://archive.org/details/completepeerageo04coka/page/357/ 357, line 16]|ps=: \"THEOBALD DILLON, 3rd s. of Thomas D. of Ballynakill, by Mary, da. of Christopher Dillon, of Kilmore ...\"}} His father was the eldest son of his grandfather James Dillon, nicknamed ''the Prior'',{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/173/ 173, line 24]|ps=: \"... he [James Dillon] obtained a temporary lease of divers Monasteries ... he was nicknamed ''the Prior'' ...\"}} because he took care of several monastic properties at the dissolution of the monasteries. His father's side of the family descended from Lord Dillon of [[Drumraney]], [[County Westmeath]]. Theobald's mother was a daughter of Christopher Dillon of Kilmore.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTELodge1789[httpsarchiveorgdetailspeerageofireland04lodgpage174 174, line 7]\"/> His father's family as his mother's family were branches of the same widespread [[Normans in Ireland|Old English]] family that descends from Sir Henry Dillon who came to Ireland with [[John, King of England|Prince John]] in 1185.{{sfn|Webb|1878|p=[https://archive.org/details/acompendiumiris00webbgoog/page/n157/ 149, line 7]|ps=: \"... [Sir Henry Dillon] came to Ireland in 1185 as secretary to Prince John ...\"}}\n\nTheobald appears below among his brothers as the third son: \n#Gerald;{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/174/ 174, line 14]|ps=: \"Gerald, who married Cicely ...\"}}\n#Edmund;{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/174/ 174, line 23]|ps=: \"Edmund, who settled in the castle of Ardnegragh, in county of Westmeath ...\"}}\n#''' Theobald''' (died 1624), the subject of this article;\n#Garret, a captain of an independent troop, ancestor of [[Garrett Dillon]], [[Recorder of Dublin]].{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/175/ 175, line 22]|ps=: \"Garret, who was Captain of an independent company in the reign of Q. Elizabeth ...\"}} and\n#James, from whom descend the Dillons of Ballynakill and some other Dillon cadet branches.{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/177/ 177, line 7]|ps=: \"James, the fifth and youngest son of Thomas, was father of James who lived in the reign of James I. and was seated at Carrownegarry, in county Roscommon; ... from this branch descended the families of Ballynakill, Tully, Portmore, Rathmoyle, Cloontowart ...\"}}\n\nTheobald had three sisters:\n#Rose, who married Thomas Dillon, son and successor to Gerald of Drumrany;{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/174/ 174, line 10]|ps=: \"Rose, married to Thomas Dillon, son and successor to Gerald, of Drumrany ...\"}}\n#Catherine, who married Edmund Fitz-Edmund Dillon of Kilcomane;{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/174 174, line 11]|ps=: \"Catherine, to Edmund Fitz-Edmund Dillon of Kilcomane;\"}} and\n#Bridget, who married a Dalton of Moyvannane.{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/174/ 174, line 12]|ps=: \"Bridget, to ___ Dalton of Moyvannane.\"}}\n\n<div style=\"float: right; margin: 0 0 0 1em\">\n{{chart top|width=auto|collapsed=no|Family tree}}\n{{chart/start|style=clear: both; font-size: 80%; width: 40em;}}\n{{chart|Txt|Txt=Theobald Dillon with wife, parents, and other selected relatives.|boxstyle_Txt=border: 0 solid white; padding-bottom: 1em; text-align: left;}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart/start|style=font-size: 70%;}}\n{{chart|GrdDl|y|Ismay|boxstyle=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em;\n |GrdDl='''Gerald<br>Dillon of<br>Dunimoney'''\n |Ismay='''Ismay<br>Tuite}}\n{{chart| | | |)|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|.}}\n{{chart| | | Rbt | |JmsDl|y|CthDn| | Wlm |boxstyle=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em;\n |Rbt='''Robert<br>Dillon'''<br>{{midsize|of Dunimoney}}\n |JmsDl='''James<br>Dillon'''<br>{{midsize|The Prior}}\n |CthDn='''Catherine<br>Dalton'''\n |Wlm='''William<br>Dillon'''}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | |!}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | |ThsDl|y|Mrgry|boxstyle=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em;\n |ThsDl='''Thomas<br>Dillon'''\n |Mrgry='''Margery<br>Dillon'''}}\n{{chart| |,|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|v|-|^|-|-|-|-|-|v}}\n{{chart|Gerld| |Edmnd| |ThbD1|y|Elnor| |Garrt|boxstyle=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em;\n |Gerld='''Gerald<br>Dillon'''\n |Edmnd='''Edmund<br>Dillon'''\n |ThbD1=[[Theobald Dillon, 1st Viscount Dillon|Theobald<br>'''1st<br>Viscount''']]<br>{{midsize|d. 1624}}|boxstyle_ThbD1=border: 2px solid red; border-radius: 0.5em; background: lavender;\n |Elnor='''Eleanor<br>Tuite'''<br>{{midsize|d. 1638}}\n |Garrt='''Garret<br>Dillon'''<br>{{midsize|Captain}}}}\n{{chart| |,|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|v|-|^|-|-|-|-|-|v| }}\n{{chart|Chrst|y|Janet| |Lucas|y|JaneM| |JmsDl|boxstyle=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em;\n |Chrst='''Christopher<br>Dillon of<br>Ballylaghan'''<br>{{midsize|d. 1624}}\n |Janet='''Janet<br>Dillon'''<br>{{midsize|m. 1604}}\n |Lucas='''Lucas<br>Dillon of<br>Loughglynn'''\n |JaneM='''Jane<br>Moore'''\n |JmsDl=[[James Dillon (officer)|'''James<br>Dillon''']]<br>{{midsize|c. 1600 \u2013<br>aft. 1669}}}}\n{{chart| |,|-|^|-|v|-|-|-|.| |`|-|.}}\n{{chart|LcsD2| |ThsD4| |ThbDl| |RbtDl|y| Ros |boxstyle=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em;\n |LcsD2=Lucas<br>'''2nd<br>Viscount'''<br>{{midsize|1610\u20131629}}|boxstyle_LcsD2=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em; background: lavender;\n |ThsD4=[[Thomas Dillon, 4th Viscount Dillon|Thomas<br>'''4th<br>Viscount''']]<br>{{midsize|1615\u20131673}}|boxstyle_ThsD4=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em; background: lavender;\n |ThbDl='''Theobald<br>Dillon'''\n |RbtDl='''Robert<br>Dillon<br>of<br>Loughglynn'''<br>{{midsize|d. 1691}}\n |Ros='''Rose<br>Dillon<br>of<br>Streams-<br>town'''}}\n{{chart| |!| | | |!| | | |!| | | |,|-|'| | | }}\n{{chart|ThbD3| |ThsD5| |LcsD6| |ThbD7|y| Mry |boxstyle=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em;\n |ThbD3=Theobald<br>'''3rd<br>Viscount'''<br>{{midsize|1629\u20131630}}|boxstyle_ThbD3=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em; background: lavender;\n |ThsD5=Thomas<br>'''5th<br>Viscount'''<br>{{midsize|d. 1674}}|boxstyle_ThsD5=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em; background: lavender;\n |LcsD6=[[Lucas Dillon, 6th Viscount Dillon|Lucas<br>'''6th<br>Viscount''']]<br>{{midsize|d. 1682}}|boxstyle_LcsD6=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em; background: lavender;\n |ThbD7=[[Theobald Dillon, 7th Viscount Dillon|Theobald<br>'''7th<br>Viscount''']]<br>{{midsize|d. 1691<br>Jacobite}}|boxstyle_ThbD7=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em; background: lavender;\n |Mry='''Mary<br>Talbot'''<br>{{midsize|d. 1691}}}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart/start|style=clear: both;}}\n{{chart|Leg|Leg='''Legend'''|boxstyle_Leg=border: 0 solid white;}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart/start|style=clear: both; font-size: 70%;}}\n{{chart|SbjBx|SbjTx| |Bk1Bx|Bk1Tx|\n |SbjBx=XXX|boxstyle_SbjBx=border: 2px solid red; border-radius: 0.5em; color: white;\n |SbjTx=Theobald<br>Dillon|boxstyle_SbjTx=border: 0 solid white; text-align: left;\n |Bk1Bx=XXX|boxstyle_Bk1Bx=background: lavender; border-radius: 0.5em; border-width: 1px; color: lavender;\n |Bk1Tx=[[Viscount Dillon|Viscounts<br>Dillon]]|boxstyle_Bk1Tx=border: 0 solid white; text-align: left;}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart/start|style=clear: both; font-size: 80%; width: 40em;}}\n{{chart|Txt|Txt=Also see the lists of siblings and children in the text.|boxstyle_Txt=border: 0 solid white; text-align: left;}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart_bottom}}\n</div>\n\nIn 1559 Theobald commanded an independent force.{{sfn|Webb|1878|p=[https://archive.org/details/acompendiumiris00webbgoog/page/n157/ 149]|ps=: \"In 1559 he commanded an independent troop in the royal cause ...\"}}\n\n==Marriage and children==\nTheobald Dillon married Eleanor Tuite. So far the sources agree. However, she is either the widow or the daughter of William Tuite according to sources.{{sfn|Burke|1832|p=[https://archive.org/details/ageneralandhera01burkgoog/page/n422 367, left column, line 4]|ps=: \"His lordship [Theobald Dillon] m. Eleanora, daughter of Sir Edward Tuite, knt., of Tuitestown, in the county of Westmeath, and widow of William Tuite of Monilea ...\"}}{{sfn|Cokayne|1916|p=[https://archive.org/details/completepeerageo04coka/page/357/ 357, line 25]|ps=: \"He [Theobald Dillon] m. Eleanor, da. of William Tuite of Tuitestown, co. Westmeath.\"}}\n\nThey had 19 children, eight sons and 11 daughters,{{sfn|Debrett|1828|p=[https://archive.org/details/debrettspeerage01debrgoog/page/n326/ 748, line 11]|ps=: \"He [Theobald Dillon] had issue 8 sons and 11 das.;\"}}\n\nThe eight sons were:{{efn|Burke (1949) mentions only Christopher and Lucas; Cokayne (1916) does not mention his children; Debrett states he had eight sons but does not give details. Lodge lists all eight sons in detail.}}\n#Christopher (died 28 February 1624), who was the eldest and married the eldest daughter of [[James Dillon, 1st Earl of Roscommon]] and became the father of the 2nd Viscount and the 4th Viscount;{{sfn|Burke|1832|p=[https://archive.org/details/ageneralandhera01burkgoog/page/n422/ 367, left column, line 9]|ps=: \"CHRISTOPHER (Sir), of Bealalahin, in the county of Mayo, who m. in 1604, Lady Jane Dillon, eldest daughter of James, first Earl of Roscommon, and dying before his father, left seven sons and five daughters.\"}}{{sfn|Cokayne|1916|p=[https://archive.org/details/completepeerageo04coka/page/357/ 357, line 33]|ps=: \"Christopher was s. and h. ap. of the last Viscount but d. v.p., 28 Feb 1623/4.\"}}\n#Lucas, ancestor of the 7th and later viscounts;{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/181/ 181, line 2]|ps=: \"Sir Lucas, from whom the present Lord Dillon descends.\"}}\n#William, styled of Tolchan;{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/181/ 181, line 4]|ps=: \"William Dillon of Tolchan, Esq; who had considerable estates assigned to him.\"}}\n#Thomas, styled of Brackloon;{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/181/ 181, line 10]|ps=: \"Thomas, on whom the estates of his nephew George devolved he was born in the Tower of London, and styled of Bracklyn or Brackloon in county of Roscomon.\"}}\n#Edward, who became a Franciscan monk;{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/182/ 182, line 38]|ps=: \"Edward and George, Friars of the Order of St. Francis.}}\n#George, who became a Franciscan monk;<ref name=\"FOOTNOTELodge1789[httpsarchiveorgdetailspeerageofireland04lodgpage182 182, line 38]\"/>\n#John, who became an officer in the army and died unmarried;{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/182/ 182, line 40]|ps=: \"John, who had a command in the army, and died unmarried}}\n#[[James Dillon (officer)|James]] (c. 1600 \u2013 1669), who was the 8th and youngest son;{{sfn|Murtagh|2004|p=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_0198613660/page/210/ 210, right column]|ps=: \"... army officer, was probably born at Kilfaughny, co. Westmeath, the eighth and youngest son of nineteen children of Theobald, first Viscount Dillon ... \"}}\n\nThe eleven daughters were:\n#Rose, who died young; {{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/184/ 184, line 12]|ps=: \"Daughter Rose, who died young.\"}}\n#Margaret, who married Robert dillon of Cannestown;{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/184/ 184, line 13]|ps=: \"Margaret, married Robert Dillon of Cannestown in Westmeath&nbsp;...\"}} \n#Anne, who was the mother of [[Theobald Taaffe, 1st Earl of Carlingford]];{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/184/ 184, line 19]|ps=: \"Anne to John, Viscount Taaffe of Corran, and mother of Theobald, Earl of Carlingford.\"}}\n#Katherine, who married Sir Ulick Burke of [[Glinsk Castle|Glinsk]], 1st Baronet;{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/184/ 184, line 21]|ps=: \"Catherine to Sir Ulick Bourke of Glinsk in the county of Roscomon, Bart.\"}}\n#Mary, who married Gerald Pettyt of [[Mullingar]] in County Westmeath;{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/184/ 184, line 23]|ps=: \"Mary, to Gerald Pettyt of Irishtown or Molyngar in Westmeath&nbsp;...\"}}\n#Elizabeth, to Thomas Fitzgerald of Newcastle in County Longford;{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/184/ 184, line 30]|ps=: \"Elizabeth,  to Thomas Fitzgerald of Newcastle, in county of Longford&nbsp;...\"}}\n#Jane, who married Hugh O'Conor of Castlereagh.{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/184/ 184, line 36]|ps=: \"Jane to Hugh O'Connor Dunn of Castlereagh in Roscommon ...\"}}\n#Ellen (died 1629), who became a nun with the [[Poor Clares]];{{sfn|Clarke|2004|p=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_0198613660/page/203/ 203, left column, line 20]|ps= \"Having arrived in Dublin on 13 June 1629, they established themselves in Merchant's Quay. As her sister Eleanor died soon after her return to Ireland, it was Cecily Dillon who was elected abbess&nbsp;...\"}}{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/184/ 184, line 38]|ps=: \"Ellen, Cecilia, Nuns of the Order of St. Clare, and who established the Franciscan order of nuns in Galway.\"}}\n#[[Cecily Dillon|Cecily]] (c. 1603 \u2013 1653), who became the first Abbess of the Poor Clares in Ireland;<ref name=\"FOOTNOTELodge1789[httpsarchiveorgdetailspeerageofireland04lodgpage184 184, line 38]\"/>{{sfn|Chambers|1882|p=[https://archive.org/details/TheLifeOfMaryWardV1/page/n266/ 198, line 16]|ps=: \"In the year 1625 six nuns left the Gravelines convent for that country [Ireland] ... Two of them were daughters of Viscount Dillon ... Mary Joseph and Cicely Francis.\"}}{{sfn|Clarke|2004|p=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_0198613660/page/202/ 202]|ps= \"Dillon, Cecily (c 1603 \u2013 1653). Poor Clare abbess&nbsp;...\"}}\n#Bridget, who died unmarried; and {{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/184/ 184, line 41]|ps=: \"Bridget, and Barbara, died unmarried.\"}}\n#Barbara, who died unmarried.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTELodge1789[httpsarchiveorgdetailspeerageofireland04lodgpage184 184, line 41]\"/>\n\n==Later life==\nIn 1582 in the context of the [[Composition of Connacht]], a [[surrender and regrant]] action, Dillon was appointed collector-general of the composition money in Connacht and [[Thomond]].{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/177 177, line 18]|ps=: \"... was appointed by patent, General Collector and Receiver of all and singular the Composition Money, within the provinces of Connaught and Thomond.\"}} During this period of the English reconquest in Connacht, Dillon was involved in some sharp practices with the local landholders. In particular he persuaded the various [[Costello (surname)|Costello]] freeholders of the [[Barony of Costello]] in eastern [[County Mayo]], to save expense and ensure the smooth legal transfer, to allow him to surrender their lands for them in one land-title in the [[Surrender and regrant]] process and had it regranted in his own name, becoming the legal landowner in the process. He never returned this title to the lands to the native owners, which would lead to [[rapparee]] actions by [[Dubhaltach Caoch Mac Coisdealbhaigh|Dudley Costello]] (or Costellogh) against the Dillons in the 1760s.{{sfn|Moody|Martin|Byrne|2009|p=[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=5zov9-tSFCoC&pg=PA448 448, line 27]|ps=: \"Dudley Costello, the most celebrated of the Connacht tories, was an 'ensignman' whose estate was held by Lord Dillon, against whom he conducted a vigorous private war.\"}}\n\nHe fought under [[Robert Devereux, 2nd Earl of Essex|the Earl of Essex]] in the [[Nine Years' War (Ireland)|Nine Years' War]] (1593\u20131603) and was knighted by him on 24 July 1599.{{sfn|Cokayne|1916|p=[https://archive.org/details/completepeerageo04coka/page/357/ 357, line 21]|ps=: \"... took an active part against the rebel Irish under Tyrone, 1598\u20131601; knighted by the Earl of Essex, 24 July 1599.\"}}{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/177/ 177, line 31]|ps=: \" ... and in 1559, received the honour of Knighthood in the field of battle.\"}}{{efn|Lodge give this year as 1559, which seems to be an error.}} To put this into perspective it should be said that Theobald was already in his sixties and that Essex knighted a great many people and was mocked by saying \"he never drew sword but to make knights\".{{sfn|Hammer|2004|p=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_0198613652/page/957/ 957, left column]|ps=: \"Already angry over the vast cost of his expedition, she was further enraged by Essex's profligacy in bestowing knighthoods ...\"}}\n\nOn 19 July 1608, [[King James I of England|King James I]] gave him a patent confirming the possession of the manor and town of Kilfaughny in County Westmeath{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/178/ 178, line 19]|ps=: \"The King also ... did by patent 19 July 1608, 6 of his reign, regrant, sell, and confirm to him, his heirs and assignes forever, the entire manor, castle, or stone-fort and town of Killenfaghny ... \"}} where he then lived and finally died.\n\nOn 16 March 1622, [[James I of England|King James I]] created him Viscount Dillon of Costello-Gallen, cementing his legal title. He became the first of a long succession of [[Viscounts Dillon|viscounts Dillon]]. [[Gallen (barony)|Gallen]] and [[Costello (barony)|Costello]] form the title's territorial designation. They are baronies of County Mayo.{{sfn|Lodge|1789|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/177/ 177, line 35]|ps=: \"... creating him Viscount Dillon of Costello-Gallen in the Kingdom of Ireland, by letters patent bearing date at Westminster, 16 March 1621-2 ...\"}}\n\nLord Dillon, as he now was, held the title of [[Lord President of Connaught]] from c. 1621 on, which he shared with [[Charles Wilmot, 1st Viscount Wilmot|Charles Wilmot]] from 1616\u20131644.{{sfn|Pollard|1900|p=[https://archive.org/details/dictionarynatio13stepgoog/page/n72 60, left column]|ps=: \"On 3 June 1616 he [Charles Wilmot] was appointed president of Connaught.\"}}\n\n==Death and succession==\nLord Dillon died on 15 March 1624{{sfn|Debrett|1828|p=[https://archive.org/details/debrettspeerage01debrgoog/page/n326/ 748, line 9]|ps=: \"... and d. 15 March 1624 ...\"}} in Kilfaughny in County Westmeath. It is said that he died \"at so advanced an age, that at one time he had the satisfaction of seeing above an hundred of his descendants in his house of Killenfaghny.\"{{sfn|Webb|1878|p=[https://archive.org/details/acompendiumiris00webbgoog/page/n157/ 149, right column, line 38]|ps=Cited in the text}} Christopher, his eldest son, died on 28 February<ref name=\"FOOTNOTECokayne1916[httpsarchiveorgdetailscompletepeerageo04cokapage357 357, line 33]\"/> about two weeks before his father and therefore never succeeded his father. On the first Viscount's death, the title therefore passed to his grandson Lucas, Christopher's eldest son.{{sfn|Burke|1832|p=[https://archive.org/details/ageneralandhera01burkgoog/page/n422/ 367, left column, line 26]|ps=: \"He [the 1st Viscount] was s. by his grandson LUCAS, second viscount ...\"}}\n\n{| {{Table|hide}}\n!colspan=3|Timeline\n|-\n|colspan=3|''As the birth date is uncertain, so are the ages.''\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Age!!align=\"left\"|Date!!align=\"left\"|Event\n|-\n|0||1530, about||Born.{{efn|name=YearB}}\n|-\n|29||1559||Commanded an independent force.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEWebb1878[httpsarchiveorgdetailsacompendiumiris00webbgoogpagen157 149]\"/>\n|-\n|52||1582||Made collector-general of the composition money.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTELodge1789[httpsarchiveorgdetailspeerageofireland04lodgpage177 177, line 18]\"/>\n|-\n|69||1599, 24 Jul||Knighted by [[Robert Devereux, 2nd Earl of Essex|Essex]].<ref name=\"FOOTNOTECokayne1916[httpsarchiveorgdetailscompletepeerageo04cokapage357 357, line 21]\"/>\n|-\n|78||1608, 19 Jul||[[King James I of England|James I]] gave him a patent for Kilfaughny house.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTELodge1789[httpsarchiveorgdetailspeerageofireland04lodgpage178 178, line 19]\"/>\n|-\n|91||1622, 16 Mar||Created Viscount Dillon of Costello-Gallen.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTELodge1789[httpsarchiveorgdetailspeerageofireland04lodgpage177 177, line 35]\"/>\n|-\n|93||1624, 28 Feb||His eldest son, Christopher, died.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTECokayne1916[httpsarchiveorgdetailscompletepeerageo04cokapage357 357, line 33]\"/>\n|-\n|93||1624, 15 Mar||He died and was succeeded by his grandson [[Lucas Dillon, 2nd Viscount Dillon|Lucas]].<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEDebrett1828[httpsarchiveorgdetailsdebrettspeerage01debrgoogpagen326 748, line 9]\"/>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Viscount Dillon]]\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{Notelist|refs=\n:{{efn|name=YearB|Theobald's year of birth is set at very roughly 1530 as he died in 1624 at an very advanced age, which is interpreted to mean that he was in his 90s.}}\n}}\n{{Reflist}}\n*{{citation|last=Burke |first=John |author-link=John Burke (genealogist) |date=1832 |title=A General and Heraldic Dictionary of the Peerage and Baronetage of the British Empire |edition=4th |volume=1 |publisher=Henry Colburn and Richard Bentley |publication-place=London |url=https://archive.org/details/ageneralandhera01burkgoog/}} \u2013 Abdy to Hutchinson\n*{{citation|last=Chambers |first=Mary Catherine Elizabeth |date=1882 |title=The Life of Mary Ward (1585\u20131645) |volume=1 |publisher=Burns and Oates |publication-place=London |url=https://archive.org/details/TheLifeOfMaryWardV1/}}\n*{{citation|last=Clarke |first=Frances |editor-last=Matthew |editor-first=Colin |editor-link=Colin Matthew |editor2-last=Harrison |editor2-first=Brian |editor2-link=Brian Harrison (historian) |date=2004 |title=Dillon, Cecily (c. 1603 \u2013 1653 ) |encyclopedia=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography |volume=16 |publisher=[[